<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT September 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here Monday that the
cooperative relations between China and Russia are conducive to
peace and stability in the region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Anatoly
Chubais, Li said Sino-Russian relations have developed well in
recent years as the two countries have scored progress in their
cooperation in various areas. (China-Premier-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russia-U.S. Commission for Economic and
Technological Cooperation opened its 9th session here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Opening the session, Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin
said the "monumental task" for the commission is the
implementation of the Helsinki economic initiative launched by
Russian and U.S. presidents Boris Yeltsin and Bill
Clinton. (Russia-US-Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Monday embarked on a
three-day visit to Moscow that is aimed to reinvigorate economic
ties, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The visit, at the invitation of Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, is the first by an Arab leader in six years to Moscow
after the former Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.
(Egypt-Russia-Mubarak Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Chinese Vice Premier Zhu Rongji delivered a
keynote speech at an international seminar on China's economic
development in the next century Monday.
</P>
<P>
In his speech entitled "The Economic Situation and Development
Prospects in China," Zhu announced that China will continue to
follow unswervingly the opening-up policy and march to the world
even more confidently.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that China will introduce certain policy incentives
towards the import of equipment needed for foreign-invested
projects that meet requirements. (Hong Kong-Zhu-Seminar)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean prosecutors demanded Monday a seven-year
jail term as well as huge fines for president Kim Young-sam's son,
Kim Hyun-chul, on charges of receiving bribes and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Prosecutor's office demanded Junior Kim 1.5 billion
won (1.67 million U.S. dollars) in fines on alleged tax evasion
and ordered return of an additional 3,274.2 million won (3.82
million dollars) on alleged bribes. (SKorea-Kim-Sentence) 
</P>
</TEXT>
