<HEADLINE> Seminar: China's Environment Has Bright Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China's environment
condition will have a bright future despite the grim situation it
presently faces, according to panelists of a seminar held here
today.
</P>
<P>
Being one of a series of seminars held before the World
Bank/International Monetary Fund (IMF) annual meetings, the
seminar entitled "China's Environment: Growing Greener?" is
especially devoted to China's environment protection issues.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, director of China National Environmental
Protection Administration, briefed participants on the present
situation of China's environment, the efforts China has made in
environment protection and the prospects of China's environment.
</P>
<P>
He said that historically rapid economic growth generally
causes serious deterioration of environmental quality, but the
fact of China tells a different story. With rapid economic growth
over the past years, China has basically averted the situation of
relatively abrupt deterioration.
</P>
<P>
"The reasons underlying this fact are that since the early
1980s, the Chinese government has adopted a series of policies and
measures for environmental protection, pushed vigorously the
coordination of environment and economic development, and
initially conceived a way of environmental protection based on
China's national conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the actions and achievements in China's
environmental protection indicate that China has both the
confidence and the capabilities to prevent and solve the
environmental problems resulting from economic development and
those left from history.
</P>
<P>
"The series of general and specific policies of environmental
protection and the strategy of coordinated development of
environment and economy carried out by China have been proved
correct and effective," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Xie also urged developed countries to do their part, as they
have promised, in helping developing countries solve their
environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Steer, panelist of the seminar and a senior official
with the World Bank, said that the Chinese government is taking
the environmental issues very seriously. China is facing serious
environmental problems and the job ahead is very difficult.
</P>
<P>
However, there is a lot of ground for hope, he said, adding
that in addition to domestic efforts, China has been promoting
international cooperation in solving environmental problems and
has been borrowing money from the World Bank to address these
issues.
</P>
<P>
He said he is optimistic about China's ability to carry out its
policies concerning environment protection.
</P>
<P>
William K. Reilly from the United States said that the Chinese
government has given top priority to environment protection and
has adopted a series of measures to address environmental
problems, which provide a lot of hope for this sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
