<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel Defends Germany's Treatment to Scientology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel today defended Germany's treatment to the Scientology
movement, saying the criticism by a U.S. senator was "intolerable"
to such a free country as Germany.
</P>
<P>
"The accusation that Scientology is being persecuted here is
absurd," Kinkel said in a statement in response to the claims by
U.S. Senator Alfonse D'Amato that Germany was restricting freedom
of religion with regard to Scientology.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel stressed, "Scientology is not a religion or world
outlook. Its goals are directed at economic activity."
</P>
<P>
He added that there were more and more signs that the
organization harassed its members and their families with
quasi-totalitarian methods.
</P>
<P>
In Germany, lawmakers have called for legislation to mandate
federal surveillance of Scientology by domestic security service.
</P>
</TEXT>
