<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Studying Party Congress Documents (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Qin Zhenhua, a Congress delegate and Party secretary of
Zhangjiagang, a city renowned for its cultural and ethical
progress and material civilization, presided over a study meeting
just after returning from Beijing. People have been encouraged to
get on with their efforts to build these two parts of society, he
reports.
</P>
<P>
"In so far as I understand the report, we should encourage
farmers to get rich, but should also help them to learn more about
science, technology, and to be more cultured," said Tang Chengqi,
head of Hufang Township, in Jiangxi province's Nanchang city.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Kong Lingren, 73-year-old vice-chairman of the Central
Committee of the China Democratic League, has been a life-long
witness to the CPC's success in liberating the Chinese people and
in showing them the way to a better life. "The Democratic League
will join hands with the CPC to enter the 21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
Members of China's ethnic minorities in autonomous regions have
also held heated discussions about the resolutions adopted at the
Congress. "The report has clearly shown that efforts must be made
to consolidate and develop equality, unity, and mutual aid among
different ethnic groups to seek a common prosperity," says
Tarqing, deputy director of the Tibet region's Commission of
Nationalities and Religious Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Different ethnic groups live peacefully in Xinjiang and local
people enjoy religious freedom. This is the victory of the Party's
policies for ethnic minorities," says Xirip Mullah, a deputy
director of the Xinjiang region's Islamic Association, in
northwest China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
