<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Cypriot Communities Leaders to Meet Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of the two
Cypriot communities will meet Friday again to discuss security
issues concerning Cyprus problem without preconditions and
without an agenda, it was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the U.N. mission in Cyprus said
that President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash will meet in the presence of chief of U.N. mission
Gustave Feissel.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that the meeting will be held at Feissel's
residence in the U.N.-controlled buffer zone in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement for a meeting between the two leaders was
announced a week ago by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright during a stop over in Cyprus, after a four-day visit to
the island by U.S. State Department Special Coordinator for
Cyprus, Thomas Miller.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will take place following the failure of the
U.N.-sponsored two rounds of direct talks between Clerides and
Denktash in July and August.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides reiterated today
that the Greek Cypriot side would enter the security talks with
"good will, seriousness and responsibility."
</P>
<P>
He told his daily press briefing that Clerides was willing to
meet and discuss security issues despite Turkish threats
against Cyprus because of Cyprus' decision to deploy the
Russian-made surface-to-air missiles on this eastern
Mediterranean island, which has remained divided since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and took over 37 percent of the island
following a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
"We will not play along with the Turkish side if it is trying
to prolong the situation and torpedo efforts," the spokesman
added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has said that it would use all necessary means to block
the transfer of the Russian-made missiles to the Cypriot
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
