<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Promote Exports to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is to open its
second trade exhibition in Kenya Tuesday as part of concerted
efforts by the Asian country to promote its exports to eastern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the Pakistan Golden Jubilee Exhibition is to
provide more industrial products to people in the eastern African
region, S. Nayyar, the chief of the show, told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya is a very important market" and "full of potential" for
Pakistan, said Nayyar, also director of the Export Promotion
Bureau of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Pakistani government sees Kenya as the
gateway through which the southern Asian country can expand
markets effectively in the whole eastern African region.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has sent around 500 invitations to
prominent business figures in eastern Africa, including those
from Uganda and Tanzania, to attend the four-day fair, he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 53 Pakistani exhibitors have put on display goods
such as air conditioners, domestic electronic gadgets,
agricultural implements, pharmaceuticals and fashion apparel.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Pakistan and Kenya is in favor of the latter,
which exported goods worth 89.8 million U.S. Dollars to Pakistan
compared to 65 million Dollars in imports in the fiscal year
ending in July, Nayyar quoted data from his government as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Pakistan's exports to Kenya shot up by 124 percent in
the year from some 27 million Dollars in the previous fiscal
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's exports to Pakistan include tea, hides and skins,
sisal, fibers, natural gum-Arabic and tanned leather. Pakistan is
the largest consumer of Kenyan tea.
</P>
<P>
Imports from Pakistan consist of rice, fertilizers, medicines,
textile yarn, cotton fabrics, carpets and glassware.
</P>
</TEXT>
