<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lilich And Coalition Lead in Serbian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Zoran Lilich and his ruling
leftist coalition took lead in the Serbian presidential and
parliamentary elections held on Sunday in Smederevo, a city south
to Belgrade, the Tanjug news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
By early morning today, Lilich had won 39 percent of the 1.87
million votes already counted while the parliamentary candidates
from the coalition had acquired 38 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
Vojislav Seselj, the candidate of the Serbian Radical Party,
obtained 30 percent of the votes accounted, according to
Tanjug. Seselj's party also secured 30 percent of the votes
accounted in the parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The voting started at 7 a.m. (0500 GMT) and ended at 8
p.m. (1800 GMT) in a peaceful atmosphere. More than half of the
7.14 million Serbian voters were estimated to have cast their
votes in the elections, in which a president and 250 parliament
members are expected to be elected.
</P>
<P>
A total of 345 foreign observers supervised the elections,
among whom 203 were from the European Security Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
