<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Italy Intend to Develop Industrial Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- France and Italy intend to
develop industrial cooperation in the aeronautics industry and
railways, including the construction of a TGV bullet train between
the Italian city of Turin and the French city of Lyons.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac and Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi agreed today to focus the next Franco-Italian summit
to be held in early October in Chambery, France, on industrial
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting in Paris today, they also reaffirmed the
attachment by France and Italy to "the strict respect" of the
Maastricht treaty, especially its timetable and criteria, said the
French presidential office.
</P>
<P>
Chirac again expressed his wish that as many countries as
possible can enter the European monetary union in the first wave
in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the expansion of the European Union (EU),
the reform of EU institutions, Italy's joining into the Schengen
convention which abolishes border control among EU countries, and
relations between the EU and the Western European Union, a defense
group joined by 10 Western European countries.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that he and French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
reached agreement over the European single currency, the need to
include a social chapter in the Maastricht treaty, and the future
European Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
"We have noted a unity of position of the two countries on
single currency and the social policy," said Prodi.
</P>
<P>
Prodi and Jospin also discussed cooperation between the police
force of the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
