<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Launches New Britain Tourism Marque </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The British Tourist
Authority's (BTA) new tourism marque for Britain is unveiled today
by Chris Smith, secretary of state for culture in London's
Trafalgar Square.
</P>
<P>
The marque has been created to represent Britain as a whole and
to reflect the English, Scottish and Welsh identities.
</P>
<P>
It has strong design elements which create a sense of unity and
ensure maximum impact and awareness of the destination name.
</P>
<P>
The new marque, designed by the London creative agency, Real
Time, will brand all BTA overseas campaigns -- ranging from the
Great British Heritage Pass and Britain's Gardens to Rock &AMP; Pop
and Style &AMP; Design.
</P>
<P>
It will also be used in all print and promotional materials.
</P>
<P>
Launching the new tourism marque, David Quarmby, BTA chairman,
said, "At its heart is the Union flag, which is recognized
throughout the world and reflects the traditional heritage of
Britain."
</P>
<P>
Britain's tourism industry is worth nearly 40 billion pounds
(64 billion US dollars) a year in revenue, including 15.4 billion
pound (24.6 billion US dollar) foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that overseas visitors to Britain in 1997 are
expected to produce another record year with visits at 25.8
million, up 2 percent, and spending up 5 percent to 12.9 billion
pounds (20.6 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Average annual growth rates from 1996 to 2000 are put at 9.3
percent in revenue, reaching 18 billion pounds (28.8 billion US
dollars) by 2000, and 4.5 percent in visits, totaling 31 million.
</P>
<P>
However, BTA chief executive Anthony Sell said, "If Britain is
to retain and improve its market share, we must capture the
imagination of potential visitors and offer them the motivation to
travel here." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
