<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Farm Ministers Warned Over Food Safety, Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- British Euro-MP Lord Plumb
warned European Union Farm Ministers today to "take tougher
measures to ensure food safety."
</P>
<P>
During an interview with BBC Radio Scotland, Plumb said, "The
EU must lead the world in setting tougher food safety regulations
and standards based on clear scientific evidence as we prepare for
the next GATT round in 1999."
</P>
<P>
"Consumer concern over recent outbreaks of E-coli and the BSE
crisis must be put to rest," stressed Plumb, who is now attending
a major world meat conference in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
As EU farm ministers gather in Brussels today to discuss food
safety agreements and BSE, Plumb attacked those in the EU and USA
who distort free trade. "To prevent future trade wars, the EU must
insure that national food safety standards abide by the GATT
principle on national treatment and non-discrimination," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Food safety regulations with no scientific basis must not be
allowed to prevent free trade. If consumer confidence worldwide is
to return, we must set clear standards," noted Plumb.
</P>
<P>
On BSE, Plumb said, "The recent move by the EU Scientific
Veterinary Committee is welcome. Farm ministers must now accept
Britain's success in tackling BSE and move swiftly to lift the ban
on British beef."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the effect of EU enlargement on rural development,
Plumb said, "Europe must not ignore the needs of the rural areas
and a quarter of Europe's population."
</P>
<P>
"History reminds us that we neglect our farms and food
production at our peril," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
