<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres to Launch Peace Center in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEL AVIV, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli prime
minister Shimon Peres announced here today that he would open a
peace center next month to make contributions to the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in Tel Aviv, Peres said the
Peres Center for Peace would be formally inaugurated on October
20 in a ceremony to be attended by many famous statesmen and
business leaders from around the world.
</P>
<P>
Peres said that the center, a non-governmental and non-profit
organization, will focus its activities on pushing for economic
cooperation between Israel and Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The peace process is basically an "economic exercise," and
would shift its focus from political monoply to economic emphasis
in order to achieve a better life for all peoples in the
region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe we have discovered many opportunities that we were
not aware beforehand and we do believe that this center can offer
real contributions to the peace process even at time of crisis
and time of desperation," Peres noted.
</P>
<P>
The center, established with the knowledge of the current
government, which he said looks upon the center favorably, would
keep in touch with other peace organizations to push forward the
peace process, Peres said, but adding that it would not be
actively involved in politics.
</P>
<P>
The long list of the center's International Board of Governors
comprises a number of former world leaders, including former
U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros Ghali, former
U.S. president Jimmy Carter, former U.S. Secretary of State
Warren Christopher, former Soviet Union leader Mikhail
Gorbachev, current French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and
Speaker of Palestinian Council Ahmed Queria.
</P>
<P>
Peres, a leading architect of the Israeli-Arab peace process,
was defeated in the May 1996 general elections by Likud leader
Benjamin Netanyahu. In June this year, he stepped down as the
leader of Labor Party and was replaced by former Army Chief of
Staff Ehud Barak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
