<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Program Launched to Promote Africa's Fruit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Brussels-based center for the
Development of Industry (CDI) has, in conjunction with the Zimbabwe
Investment Center, launched a program to promote the export of
processed fruit and vegetables from eastern and Southern Africa into
the European market.
</P>
<P>
About 25 exporting companies from eastern and southern Africa and
an equal number of European fruit and vegetable importers are meeting
in Zimbabwe for the CDI-sponsored industrial partnership meeting on
export opportunities for processed fruits and vegetables from the
region.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which began in Harare today will move to the eastern
resort town of Nyanga.
</P>
<P>
Delegates, comprising CDI experts, fruit and vegetable company
representatives from the EU and Kenya, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe
will visit a number of fruit processing firms before going to Nyanga.
</P>
<P>
Formed in 1977 during the first Lome Convention, the CDI is the
industrial-promotion arm of the partnership between the EU and member
countries of the African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) region.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the meeting, Zimbabwe's Secretary for Industry
and Commerce Kelebert Nkomani said the CDI is a practical
demonstration of the benefits that ACP countries are deriving from
the ACP-EU relationship.
</P>
<P>
"Fruit and vegetable-growing is a good source of employment in
the region, as most of the activities in this industry are
labour-intensive. In a region where unemployment levels are high,
the industry fulfills an urgent social need," Nkomani said.
</P>
<P>
CDI divisional head for technical services and EU networks Daniel
Nairac said the organization was involved in seeking ways to add
value to industrial raw materials from the ACP countries as a way of
generating employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
