<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RQAN Helps Qualified Africans Go Back Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Return and Integration of
Nationals Program (RQAN) has assisted more than 1,500 qualified
Africans to return and take up employment in key sectors of their
countries' economies since its launch in 1983.
</P>
<P>
The program, which is being implemented by the International
Organisation For Migration (IOM) in conjunction with
participating African governments, seeks to bring to an end the
brain drain on the continent and strengthen direct contribution
the trained and experienced African nationals abroad can make
towards development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
IOM spokesman Thomas Weiss said the program aimed at promoting
the return of qualified migrant Africans to or relocate them
within Africa so that their knowledge could be used towards the
development of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Weiss was speaking during the Southern African Regional
Institute For Policy Studies (SARIPS) and Southern African
Political and Economic Series (SAPES) Colloquium which started
here today.
</P>
<P>
Africa faces a brain drain problem which is worsened by poor
salaries and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
RQAN, which was launched in 1983 with assistance from the
Ruropean Union, is currently working with 10 African countries to
try and lure African professionals living abroad to return home.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 colloquium, which is the 10th to be organised by
SAPES and SARIPS, seeks to enhance interaction among southern
African scholars, policy makers and technicians to promote
regular, rational and development related policy dialogue in the
region and improve understanding of the processes pertaining to
labour markets and migration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
