<HEADLINE> Israeli-Turkish Military Cooperation Not to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Ambassador to
Cyprus Semi Tzur said today that the military cooperation between
Israel and Turkey will not affect this eastern Mediterranean
island.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides, Tzur said there has been an agreement between Israel
and Turkey which concerns cooperation on military issues. However,
it should be made clear that this is not an alliance, but
cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tzur said his country has no part in the Cyprus dispute and
rejected the view that in case of military conflict on the
island Israel would go against Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli ambassador also said that his country has an
agreement with Greece for military cooperation which has been
bolstered in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Tzur and the Cypriot foreign minister
arranged a meeting between Kasoulides and his Israeli counterpart
David Levy which is scheduled to take place in New York.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers are expected to discuss the Middle East
peace process, the Turkish-Israeli military cooperation and the
joint U.S.-Turkish-Israeli military exercises due to be held in
Eastern Mediterranean in November. The upcoming exercises have
caused concern to Cyprus as well as to some other countries in the
Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey sent its troops
and took over the northern third of the island following a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
