<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stay of Prosecution Sought in Banana Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Former Zimbabwean President
Canaan Banana appeared before the High Court here today, facing
11 charges of sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
But Banana submitted that he could not be guaranteed a fair
trial because of what he termed prejudicial publicity given to
allegations against him since February this year.
</P>
<P>
Banana, Zimbabwean President from April 1980 until December
1987, is supposed to answer to two counts of sodomy, three counts
of attempted sodomy, and six charges of indecent assault.
</P>
<P>
In his submissions before Justice Blackie siting with
assessors major Misheck Nyandoro and Tuttam Chaudry, Council for
Defence advocate Chris Andersen said he was applying for a stay
of prosecution of his client because of the pre-trial publicity
which tended to be prejudicial to the former head of state and
interferred with his constitutional right to a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
Andersen told the court that the state had refused to hand
over to the defence essential documents such as the police diary
relating to the investigations of their client.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the publicity which he said prejudiced his client,
Andersen referred to various press publications and headlines one
of which read: ''Banana Sex Scandal Baloons''.
</P>
<P>
''The nature of the reporting projudiced the accused having a
fair trial,'' argued Andersen.
</P>
<P>
''The totality of these passages plainly suggests that the
accused has been guilty of a number of charges. Together with
the state outline it does irreparable harm to the accused,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''The only remedy would be a stay of prosecution.
The damage could not be undone by making it being referred to
another court because of the very wide publicipy by virtue of
newspaper reports and state outline.''
</P>
<P>
Rebutting Andersen's application, Director of Public
Prosecutions Augustine Chikumira pointed out that in any case the
High Court did not have the jurisdiction to order a stay of
prosecution. Only the supreme courty could do that, he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0026 </DOCNO>
