<HEADLINE> Portugal, Mozambique to Tighten Military Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Portugal and Mozambique have
decided today to strengthen their military cooperation ties,
especially in the military training and safeguarding of their
territorial sea.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint communique issued after the meeting
between Mozambican Defense Minister Aguiar Mazula and visiting
Portuguese counterpart Antonio Vitorino, the two countries are to
materialize their cooperation programs in a framework plan.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the two defense ministers examined
the Lisbon Joint Communique signed between the two countries in
April 1994, and agreed to quicken the implementation of the
planned cooperation programs in the military field.
</P>
<P>
As to airforce cooperation, Mazula said that before they make
any decision for further cooperations, the two sides would have a
joint investigation into the current airforce status, especially
the situation with the former Soviet Union-trained personnel and
the Soviet Union made equipment.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers agreed that they could make use of the
military training centers in Maputo and Nacala (in Nampula
Pprovince ) training centers as basis for training soldiers for
other Portuguese-speaking countries in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese minister, who has visited the two centers, said
that the centers have all the conditions necessary for military
training cooperation among the African Portuguese-speaking
countries.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Portuguese defense minister was also met by the
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano at Massinga County in
southern Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Antonio is scheduled to leave for Lisbon today after his
week-long visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
