<HEADLINE> US President Addresses UN Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton stressed here today his support for the United Nations'
role on peace and freedom, but with little promise on paying out
all its huge sum of debts owed to this largest international
organization.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 52nd General Assembly session, the U.S.
president said that the United States strongly supports the
leadership of Secretary General Kofi Annan in his pursuit of the
U.N. reform which he described as the "most far reaching." He said
the U.S. will pass the secretary general's reform agenda for this
session.
</P>
<P>
But he did not mention the time the U.S. will take to pay off
the more than a billion U.S. dollars it owed to the United
Nations. He said he hopes that member states will adopt a "more
equitable scale of assessment" (of their duties).
</P>
<P>
He said that the United Nations has a special responsibility to
help make sure that the global economy creates greater wealth, it
"does not produce growing disparities between the haves and
have-nots."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also voiced the support of his country for expanding
the Security Council of the U.N.
</P>
<P>
In his 27-page speech, the president also mentioned the fast
development of technology, which he indicated has benefited
mankind throughout the world, but also has been taken use of by
criminals who abused the vast power of technology to engage in
different kinds of international crime such as terrorism, drug
trafficking and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
The president called for worldwide efforts to continue to
prevent conflict, promote international human rights standards and
move people from poverty to dignity and prosperity through
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
On peace and security, he said, conflicts between nations, and
within nations, have cost 20 million lives. Clinton expressed his
appreciation for the United Nations' efforts to keep many nations
away from bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the importance of eliminating weapons of mass
destruction. "We cannot allow them to fall or remain in the wrong
hands," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
