<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Turns Down UAE Territorial Claim on Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran today rejected once
again the territorial claim by the United Arab Emirates (UAE) over
three islands in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing here, Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud
Mohammadi expressed Iran's regret over the UAE's claim over three
islands of Greater and Lesser Tunbs and Abu Musa.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that it is not proper for Iran's Arab
neighbor to raise the dispute at a time when Muslims are facing
various conspiracies and maneuvers of the Israeli regime.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the three Persian Gulf islands belong to
Iran, terming the raising of the issue as "a divisive move" which
serves the plots of the Israeli regime against the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Iran is ready to hold bilateral negotiations
with the UAE to resolve misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the United Arab Emirates have been disputing since the
early 1970s over the islands, which are strategically situated at
the entrance to the Persian Gulf, opposite the Strait of Hormuz.
</P>
<P>
On November 30, 1971, one day before the British troops'
withdrawal and two days before the proclamation of the United
Emirates of Abu Dhabi, Dubai, Sharjah, Ras al-Khaimah, Fujairah,
Ajman and Umm al-Quwain, Iranian troops occupied the three
islands.
</P>
<P>
It is clear that Tehran will not make any compromise with UAE
on the sovereignty of the three islands despite the change of the
Iranian government. The territorial dispute is the main obstacle
to the improvement of relations between Iran and Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Cooperation Council, which groups the UAE, Saudi
Arabia, Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman and Qatar, has criticized Iran for
"not responding positively to calls" from the UAE to settle the
dispute over the islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian FM: No Stability Can Be Achieved With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Foreign
Minister Seyoum Mesfin has stressed that "peace and stability are
unattainable in a world where billions are under poverty line."
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency today, the remarks were
made by the minister when he left here Sunday night for New York
to attend the 52nd General Assembly of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the inflow to developed nations of trade,
resource, finance and investment shows the unbalanced economic
and business relations between developed and developing nations.
</P>
<P>
The minister said " Thirtytwo of the 38 world poorest
countries are in Africa. These countries deserve special
assistance."
</P>
<P>
He said the problem demands the support of the international
community to developing nations through debt relief and cancella-
tion as well as economic assistance meant for infrastructure and
social service expansion. Ethiopia's foreign policy focuses on
ways of benefiting from such schemes, he added. 
