<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Hails His Party's Gains in Hamburg Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
today hailed his party's gains in Hamburg elections Sunday,
expressing optimism about the general elections scheduled for
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
"I am very satisfied with the message the Hamburg voters sent
me," Kohl said. "I intend to win the (1998) elections."
</P>
<P>
Kohl is seeking a fifth four-year term in the general elections
after 15 years in office.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's regional elections in Hamburg, Germany's second
biggest city, Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU) obtained
30.7 percent of the vote, up 5.6 percent over 1993.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the main opposition Social Democrats (SPD) saw its
vote down by over 4 percent, managing to lead with 36.2 percent in
the northern port city, which is traditionally dominated by them.
</P>
<P>
Hamburg's SPD mayor, Henning Voscherau, announced his
resignation in response to the worst postwar result of his party.
</P>
<P>
The election result is viewed as a major setback to the SPD,
coming at the start of a series of regional polls leading up to
the country's general elections.
</P>
<P>
"The result is without any doubt a disappointment," said SPD
leader Oskar Lafontaine.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's elections, the environmental Greens gained 13.9
percent of the vote and are calling for a leftist coalition with
the SPD in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
The Greens also want to set up a "Red-Green" coalition in Bonn.
Opinion polls currently show such an alliance could defeat Kohl's
center-right coalition in the general elections.
</P>
<P>
The CDU has urged the SPD to set up a CDU-SPD "grand coalition"
in Hamburg, like the one in Berlin and some other German states.
</P>
<P>
The Bonn government's junior coalition partner Free Democrats
(FDP) received only 3.5 percent of the vote in the Hamburg
elections, short of the 5 percent specified by law to qualify for
seats in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The FDP has lost many regional elections in recent years,
raising the possibility that it might not be able to enter the
federal parliament in 1998 and, as a result, deprive Kohl's
coalition of majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forum to Promote Girls' Education in E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A five-day workshop on
promotion of girls' education in east African sub-region opened
here today.
</P>
<P>
The third sub-regional Forum for African Women Educationalists
(FAWE) is attended by delegates from several east African
countries including Kenya, Tanzania, Rwanda, Uganda and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the forum, Executive Director of the FAWE
Dddah Gachukia called on governments to be committed to translating
their recognition into tangible action.
</P>
<P>
She said, the acknowledgement of the value of female education
by itself is futile unless governments design viable policies and
implementation strategies to ensure increased and sustainable
enrollment for girls and women at all levels of education system
and training programs.
</P>
<P>
She said that the promotion of girls' education calls for
practical involvement of all concerned and influential bodies as
it could not be implemented only by the efforts of African women
ministers.
</P>
<P>
The goals of FAWE could best be implemented at
the national levels, she said, adding that participants returning
to their respective countries are expected to practically interpret
the terms of the forum which include capacity building for
increased coverage of girls'' and women education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
