<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Subsidies for Farmers Should Be Stopped: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South African Water and
Forestry Minister Kader Asmal said today that the practice of
letting farmers get water virtually free of charge should be stopped.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a water law workshop in Pretoria, Asmal said water
tariffs in South Africa are lower than the real value of
water, which amounted to the the subsidization of water.
</P>
<P>
"We do not subsidize fertilizer. We do not subsidize sheep. Why on
earth should we subsidize water?" he asked, noting it was becoming
difficult for the government to allow water to be used at subsidized
rate for practices resulting in the inefficient use of water.
</P>
<P>
Asmal said water subsidies should be phased out gradually and in
an orderly fashion. "We need to give farmers time to adjust, and the
ability to withstand the impacts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asmal denied that the proposed new water legislation is only aimed at
farmers, stressing new policies are being devised for all major users
of waters, including the industry, urban, and domestic consumers.
</P>
<P>
"No one will escape the need for better use of our limited water
resources," Asmal added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
