<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mad House Employees Jailed for Letting Out Bus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian prosecution has
ordered nine employees of a mental hospital be jailed for letting
loose a lunatic who was charged of bombing a tourist bus downtown
Cairo last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Counsellor Hisham Saraya, attorney-general of the Higher State
Security Prosecution, said they would be jailed for 15 days
pending investigations on charges of taking bribes to facilitate
the exit of the suspect and others from the hospital, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The jailed include three doctors at the Khanka Hospital for
Psychological and Nerve Diseases, Sayed Ahmed Al Qot, Supervisor
of Psychological Health, Nessim Abdel Malak Nessim, the hospital's
former director who was dismissed on the same day the attack took
place, and Ahmed al Haggar.
</P>
<P>
Six male nursing attendants at Khanka hospital have also been
jailed for 15 days pending investigations.
</P>
<P>
The mentally-disturbed Saber Mohamed Farahat and his brother
Mahmoud Farahat had been arrested for the shooting and petrol bomb
attack which killed nine German tourists and an Egyptian driver.
</P>
<P>
Saber was sent to the hospital in 1993 after a court ruled he
was insane after convicting him of shooting dead three foreign
tourists in a Cairo hotel. Police said he escaped three days
before the latest attack.
</P>
<P>
Investigations have revealed that the employees responsible for
the entry and exit of patients from the hospital have given Saber
a regular leave against payment of money.
</P>
<P>
Saber used to spend 20 days at home every month and five days
at the hospital. He even left the hospital five months ago to be
married at a grand wedding party attended by some doctors and
nurses from the mad house.
</P>
<P>
The Farahat brothers owned a bakery with daily profit of 400
Egyptian pounds (118 U.S. dollars). Saber said they launched the
attack to avenge the blasphemous posters against Islam in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In the aftermath of the attack, Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak has ordered the transfer of administration of lunatic
asylums nationwide from municipalities to the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Tourism Ministry reiterated today that the attack
was not "a terrorist act," but "a criminal act with no correlation
to organized terrorism" that will not affect Egypt's
multi-billion-dollar tourist industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
