<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Peacekeepers Clash With S. Leone Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping force
known as ECOMOG and troops of Sierra Leone's military junta today
traded gunfire near the airport in the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The two sides first exchanged small arms fire and then artillery
fire, said residents of the Lungi district where the airport is
located, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
No casualty was reported in today's clashes. But the state
radio and television said that an ECOMOG plane bombed a power
plant Saturday in Freetown, injuring one person and damaging the
structure.
</P>
<P>
The military seized power in a coup on May 25, ousting the
legitimate government, and the junta has formed an alliance with
ex-rebels of the Revolutionary United Front which has been fighting
successive governments in the country since 1991.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG has deployed troops in Sierra Leone to enforce a stiff
economic embargo imposed after the coup in a bid to force the junta
out of power.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between ECOMOG troops and local forces have been frequent
and the junta claims that dozens of civilians have been killed in
ECOMOG air raids or bombardments aimed mainly at boats held to be
breaching the embargo.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's west African neighbors are in New York to solicit
support from the United Nations to the embargo. UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan has reportedly pledged to back the efforts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
