<HEADLINE> Turkey Voices Opposition to Missile Deployment in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel said here today that Turkey will never accept the
deployment of anti-aircraft missiles in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the press at the airport before leaving for Croatia
for a two-day official visit, Demirel said that Turkey will do
what it can to defend its state interests, the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Turkey would seek for a diplomatic solution to
the missile crisis, but stressed that "it is impossible for
Turkey to accept the deployment of missiles in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, as two NATO member states, should play
positive roles in the settlement of the Cyprus issue, the Turkish
president said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed an agreement with Russia in January to purchase
hundreds of Russian-made S-300 missiles.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports that the anti-aircraft missiles will be
transferred to the Greek Cypriots have caused a new wave of
tension between the small island country and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karaday
reaffirmed Sunday that Turkey will use all necessary means to
block the delivery of the S-300 missiles to the Cypriot
government.
</P>
<P>
Despite Ankara's repeated accusation, the Cypriot government
argued that it bought the missiles for defense purchase, not
directed against any country.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third part of the island to
protect the Turkish Cypriots following an abortive coup by Greek
Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" which is recognized only by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
