<HEADLINE> Dodi Personally Asks Paul to Drive Car: Diana's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Trevor Rees-Jones, the
bodyguard of Princess Diana and her friend Dodi al Fayed, has
revealed that Dodi personally asked Henri Paul to drive the
Mercedes S-280 sedan in the night when the fatal accident which
killed them took place.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted reliable sources as saying
that Rees-Jones told investigating judge Herve Stephan, "Dodi
called him (Paul) in order that he conducted us from the rear gate
of the hotel."
</P>
<P>
During the first interview of him by Judge Stephan last Friday,
the 29-year-old former British parachutist, who was the only
survivor in the crash, said that they first planned to leave Ritz
Hotel in two separate cars in order to shake the photographers,
but Dodi changed mind for an unknown reason.
</P>
<P>
He also remembered that when they left the hotel, they were
followed by "one car and two motors."
</P>
<P>
"It seems to me that it was a white vehicle with a trunk which
opened at the rear, a three-door, but I can remember nothing
else," Rees-Jones was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rees-Jones suffered from serious facial injury, light brain
contusion and pulmonary contusion from the crash.
</P>
<P>
Philippe Lacert, a neurologist at the Hospital of Lariboisiere
in Paris, said that it would take 12 to 15 months for him to
regain his memory, and that it was possible for his memory to
never come back again.
</P>
<P>
The British daily Guardian reported today that there could be a
collision between the Mercedes with a Fiat Uno about 60 meters
from the entry of the underpass near the Alma Square in downtown
Paris, in which the accident took place on the early morning of
August 31.
</P>
<P>
But investigators, who are looking for a Fiat Uno which had one
tail light broken, said they have not found any evidence to prove
a collision between the Mercedes and another car.
</P>
<P>
Police found some debris from a red tail light of a Fiat Uno
near the debris of the head lights of the Mercedes, as well as
some paint on the right front side of the Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
Three weeks after the crash took place, police so far have
officially acquired two certain points: the car was speeding very
fast, and the driver, Henri Paul, was drunk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Warring Parties to Resume Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Warring parties in Sudan
today agreed to re-open face-to-face talks set here for October
28 to end their 14-year-old bloody confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mohamed, Sudan's Minister for Federal Relations, and Nhial
Deng, on behalf of the rebel Sudan People's Liberation
Moverment/Army (SPLM/SPLA), reached agreement at a ministerial
meeting of the Inter-Governmental Authority on Development
(IGAD).
</P>
<P>
Under a joint communique, the two sides re-affirmed the
Declaration of Principles made by IGAD (Intergovernmental
Authority on Development) leaders in 1994 "as the basis for
negotiations and agree to cooperate fully in the search for a
negotiated solution to the conflict."
</P>
<P>
According to the declaration, religious factor is recognized
as an important role in Sudan's development.
</P>
<P>
The one-day IGAD meeting was also attended by Kenyan Foreign
Minister Kalonzo Musyoka, Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile
Weldensae, Uganda's Acting Foreign Minister Martin Aliker and
Vice-Foreign Minister of Ethiopia Tekeda Alemu.
</P>
<P>
They urged the parties involved the Sudan conflict "to put
aside any issues that may hinder the progress of the peace
process."
</P>
<P>
"Since September 1994 when the IGAD peace initiative stalled,
the situation in southern Sudan has deteriorated considerably,"
said Musyoka at the beginning of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes the meeting "will enable the (IGAD) committee
to determine the path we should follow to push for a lasting
solution" to the crisis in Sudan "as quickly as possible."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SPLM/SPLA negotiators issued a statement to the
press after the meeting, charging that the Sudanese government
"does not seek a genuine dialogue."
</P>
<P>
The Khartoum regime "aims rather at persuading the (regional)
leaders...to gently nudge the SPLM onto its internal 'peace'
bandwagon which essentially is a unilateral peace prescription or
the regime's own position paper," Nhial said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's civil war erupted in 1983 when the SPLM/SPLA took up
arms for greater autonomy of the Christian south from the Moslem
north. All efforts to end the conflict have so far failed.
</P>
<P>
The IGAD held two high-level meetings in 1994 on the crisis in
Sudan. Since then, all IGAD peace initiatives had stalled until
July, 1997 when an IGAD summit was held here and Sudan's
government accepted the Declaration of Principles as basis for
talks.
</P>
<P>
IGAD was set up in 1986 for enhancing cooperation on
anti-drought and economic development among the member countries
-- plus Djibouti and Somalia. Regional political affairs have
been on its agenda since 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Welcomes Annan's Proposals for UN Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The report by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan entitled "The United Nations: a
Program for Reform" was timely and opportune, said Luiz
Felipe Lampreia, minister of external relations of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the general debate of the 52nd
United Nations General Assembly, the minister said the Brazilian
government welcomed the report with satisfaction and enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
Those proposals would certainly warrant close attention in the
General Assembly and in parallel consultation, and would help
consolidate a new spirit that should inspire the organization, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The new spirit is called leadership: that driving force of
history altering the course events within countries and in
international scenario, opening new horizons, giving hope to the
people of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This kind of leadership has given the world a forum without
parallel in history, a stage for negotiation and a political
force in favor of international peace and security," the foreign
minister added.
</P>
<P>
He said the United Nations had an irreplaceable role in a world
that still combined forces of integration and cooperation with
forces of disintegration and aggression.
</P>
<P>
"The past few years have shown that reform of the United
Nations can no longer be put off. We cannot lose sight of the
major institutional issues nor waste further precious energy,"
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "For the United Nations to make a difference and
provide leadership in today's complex world, it must recover the
original meaning of the Charter by concentrating on its essential
mission: maintaining international peace and security, promoting
justice and international law, strengthening cooperation for
development, protecting human rights and providing humanitarian
assistance."
</P>
<P>
On the reform of the Security Council, the minister said that
Brazil had upheld a concept of reform that would strengthen the
Security Council and the United Nations as a whole, and it was not
geared to the individual interests of any one country.
</P>
<P>
"The Council must be enlarged both in its permanent membership
-- to contemplate the industrialized and the developing worlds --
and in its non-permanent membership -- to allow for more frequent
participation by interested states," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He added, "The international community needs a strong,
efficient and ever-present United Nations. We will continue to
rely on a political body with the universality and moral strength
that only the United Nations had been able to muster in the
history of mankind." 
</P>
</TEXT>
