<HEADLINE> Liberia Cracks Down Upon Armed Robbery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Liberian police and the west
African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) killed one suspected armed
robber and arrested 20 others in weekend raids on the suburbs of
the capital Monrovia, said a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Police director Joe Tate said suspect Aloysius Kieh was shot
dead while attempting to escape in a joint police and ECOMOG
night patrols "to rid the city of armed bandits".
</P>
<P>
The police had launched "Operation Clean Monrovia to make the
city a safe place to live," Tate said, quoted by the British
Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to carry out this operation until every armed
robber is caught and brought to justice," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 400 police officers will soon be assigned to
neighborhood watch teams for crime prevention.
</P>
<P>
The neighborhood teams would jointly work with the police to
deter crime in the communities, Assistant Police Director Yvonne
Steward said.
</P>
<P>
Reports of armed robberies in the city have increased over the
last two months with at least five persons, including a
12-year-old girl, killed in such incidents.
</P>
<P>
Last month, President Charles Taylor expressed serious concern
about the reports, and ordered stte security and ECOMOG to deal
"firmly and decisively with the heinous crime".
</P>
<P>
Security is one of the major tasks of the newly-inaugurated
government in Liberia, where the seven years of civil war has
left many people in abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
The weapons of former warring factions which remain in the
hands of some individuals facilitate armed robbery in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
