<HEADLINE> US Air Force Halts Training Flight to Review Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Air Force today
suspended training flights for combat air crews at domestic bases
for 24 hours to review safety issues arising from a recent string
of accidents.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the Air Force, including transport and tanker units
and warplanes based abroad, will suspend training flights for 24
hours Friday.
</P>
<P>
After an Air Force B-1 bomber crashed last Friday, the Air
Force Combat Command decided to move up the service-wide halt of
training flights from Friday to today.
</P>
<P>
The Navy, Marine Corps and Army are scheduled to take a one-day
stand-down similar with the Air Force before the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen last week ordered a
military-wide stand-down for "a period of reflection" on safety
after a series of air accidents.
</P>
<P>
It is the first-ever suspension of all military pilot training.
Cohen's order does not affect operational flights such as those
over Iraq and in support of Bosnia peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Sunday from his headquarters at Langley
Air Force Base, Virginia, Air Combat Commander General Richard
Hawley said the one-day pause was needed to "focus intently on
what we do and how we do it."
</P>
<P>
"We need to determine why these incidents happened and how to
prevent any more mishaps," said Hawley.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military has lost a C-141 transport plane, a F-117a
stealth fighter, two F-18s, two F-16s and a B-1 bomber since
September 13 in air crashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
