<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Arabia achieved a growth rate of 8.6
percent in economy in 1996, according to the latest official
figures.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Minister of Planning Abdul-Wahab al-Attar attributed the
growth mainly to an increase in the gross domestic product of the
oil sector from 6.8 percent in 1995 to 16 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Saudi Press Agency as saying that non-oil
production witnessed a rise of 4.16 percent, while the production
of private sectors surged by 3.5 percent in 1996 due to a
recorded industrial growth rate of 11.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that Saudi Arabia had spent 640 billion
U.S. dollars in the last 27 years for social and economic
development programs.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait Stock Exchange today started showing
live daily trading deals in the Bahraini bourse via special
devices in a step towards the all-round linkage of the two
markets.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti bourse Director General Hisham Al-Otaibi said the
measure is aimed at getting Kuwaiti investors acquainted
themselves with the daily developments in Bahraini stock market
ahead of the linkage of the two bourses.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait announced Sunday the stock exchanges in the two Gulf
countries will sign an agreement Saturday to open the way for
cross trading between the two markets.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, expected to become effective early next year,
aims to link clearing houses and brokerage firms of the two
markets that will ease the way for cross trading.
</P>
<P>
A clearing house or similar body is also expected to be built
in Bahrain that will play the same role as the Kuwait Clearing
Company which guarantees share transactions here.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would be the second of its kind among stock
markets of the Gulf Cooperation Council's (GCC) states. GCC
groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Oman,
Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Oman and Bahrain have already linked their floors and a
number of companies from the two countries have been listed in
both exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Exchange officials believe that the joining together of the
Kuwaiti and Bahraini markets would encourage cross-listing of
companies and the flow of capital between the two countries, thus
boosting the economic cooperation among them.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait stock exchange has been performing well since last
year and so far more than 70 companies have been listed on the
market.
</P>
<P>
On January 6, the stock exchange markets of Kuwait, Egypt and
Lebanon were linked together via a computer network displaying
daily deals in each country.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Operation of the unified power grid between Egypt and
Jordan will start in December within the project of unifying the
eastern Arab countries in one electric network, local newspaper
the Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The network will be later connected with the European unified
grid.
</P>
<P>
Cost of the project reached 250 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
