<HEADLINE> Iraqi Cultural Festival Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BABYLON, IRAQ, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Babylon
international cultural festival, one of the largest in Arab world,
opend here this evening despite of the hardship brought by the
7-year-old U.N. sanctions imposed on the country.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,200 artists, newsmen and archaeologists from some 40
countries are attending the ten-day annual event, the 9th festival
since started in 1987, organizers told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the event, Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan said the holding of the event bespeaks Iraqi people's
determination to meet the challenges and difficulties resulted
from the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed following Iraqi invasion of
neighboring Kuwait in 1990. And the Gulf War caused twice the
suspension of the annual festival in 1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
Babylon, the ancient capital of Neo-Babylonian Empire in the
7th BC and localed 90 kilometers south of Baghdad, is one of the
most famous cities of antiquity in the world. 
</P>
