<HEADLINE> Schools Back to Business in Washington D.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 78,000 public
school students in the capital of the United States began classes
Monday, after a three-week delay to repair roofs at dozens of city
schools.
</P>
<P>
The work was part of a massive program to remedy fire code
violations that have caused delayed school openings in three of
the past four years.
</P>
<P>
Children will start school each day at 8:30 a.m., 15 minutes
earlier than usual, and end at 3:30 p.m., 15 minutes later, to
make up for the lost time.
</P>
<P>
Schools chief Julius Becton had hoped a district would allow
the students to attend classes while the repairs were under way.
As Superior Court Judge Kaye Christian denied that request, Becton
postponed the original September 2 start date.
</P>
<P>
Christian fined the school system 61,000 dollars when officials
failed to have repairs completed last week as originally promised.
The last school was cleared Friday to reopen.
</P>
<P>
The judge monitors the schools as part of a 1994 lawsuit by the
advocacy group Parents United for D.C. Schools.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
