<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Newsmen Taken to Court for Libeling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Six Egyptian reporters have
been charged of publishing stories libeling and slandering against
the Interior Minister Hassan el-Alfi of corruption.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Public Prosecutor Ragaa al-Arabi announced today that
a two-month investigation shows the stores published in Arabic
bi-weekly Al-Shaab are groundless.
</P>
<P>
Magdi Ahmed Hussein, Salah Bedewi, Adel Hussein and Hoda
Mekkawi of the bi-weekly, together with Essam Sharquwi, a
cartoonist of al-Ummah newspaper and Mohamed Hamdi al-Shami, a
freelancer, are facing charges of printing untrue stories defaming
Alfi and the police agency in Egypt, the prosecutor told the press.
</P>
<P>
The indictment sheet issued by the prosecution says that eight
issues of the bi-weekly published stories with phrases
"undermining Alfi's image, honor and reputation."
</P>
<P>
It accuses Magdi Hussein, Bedewi and Mekkawi of being contempt
of court for violating the prosecution's ban on reporting the case
by the press until the end of the investigations and printing
"baseless stories damaging the image of the police body."
</P>
<P>
Bedewi is also charged for breaching public peace by printing
groundless stories in which he claimed that the Interior Ministry
had been penetrated by a foreign intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shaab, with a circulation of about 130,000, has been
accusing Alfi and his associates of racketeering, nepotism and
involvement in a high-profile corruption case.
</P>
<P>
Alfi filed a libel suit on August 16 against Al-Shaab, accusing
it of defaming his families and his ministry. The paper then filed
a counter lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
It was the second case filed by Egypt's celebrities against the
press for slander this year.
</P>
<P>
On September 14, six reporters, three Saudis and three
Egyptians, were found guilty of libeling against Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak's two sons for defamatory stories about
their business dealings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
