<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen met with Indian Prime Minister
Inder Kumar Gujral here today and they held talks on Sino-Indian
relations and international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
China and India have made new progress in the development of
their relations of constructive partnership of cooperation since
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's state visit to India last year,
said Qian, who is here attending the 52nd session of the United
Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The two nations are working for further expansion of the
cooperation agreed by the leaders of the two countries during
Jiang's visit, which Qian said was successful and important to the
growth of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Qian briefed Gujral about the just concluded 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China. He told Gujral that the
Congress, upholding Deng Xiaoping's theory, adhered to the policy
of deepening reforms and opening up to the outside world,
safeguarding world and regional peace and stability and promoting
mutual development of nations.
</P>
<P>
Gujral said he was satisfied with the development of relations
between the two countries following Chinese President Jiang's
visit to India, and congratulated China for its resumption of the
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Hong and its successful
conclusion of the National Congress of the Communist Party of
China.
</P>
<P>
He said, Hong Hong's return to China symbolized the end of
colonialism in Asia, so it was of great importance in the history.
Indian people also expected new progress for the Chinese people
under the guidance of the spirit of the Congress, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed areas of cooperation between the
two nations and international and regional issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
Qian hoped that the South Asian nations coexist friendly and
settle their differences peacefully through talks and
consultations. 
</P>
