<HEADLINE> Britain Urges U.S. to Pay off UN Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook today urged the United States to pay its 1.5
billion U.S. dollars debts to the United Nations without
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Cook made the appeal in an interview with CNN( Cable Network
News)'s International program when U.S. President Bill Clinton was
addressing the 52nd session of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure of the conservative Republican-controlled
Congress, Clinton demand a reduction of the amount Washington
contributes to the largest international organization.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that Washington could not expect to withhold its
debts while other members both from developing countries and
developed ones have paid up in full and on time.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress has repeatedly said that it would not
authorize the Clinton administration to pay off the arreas unless
the world body had implemented reform measures and proposals set
forth by Washington.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that even if the U.N. had met the U.S. conditions,
the Congress was prepared to pay only two-thirds of the U.S.
debts.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that he would not compromise on the question of the
U.S. debts to the United Nations, although he would risk offending
the sensibilities of a major ally by naming Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We would very much like Congress to recognize...that
countries like Britain which pays in full and pays on time does
not feel it's fair when other countries--whether it's the U.S. or
anybody else--does not pay in full and does not pay on time,"
Cook said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
