<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Damages African Electronic Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Adverse weather, particularly
heavy rain, has been cited as one of the major factors to cause
damage of electronic equipment in some African countries, forcing
them to spend million of U.S. dollars to repair or replace it.
</P>
<P>
This was identified by the African energy experts, scientists
and technicians attending a five-day workshop to discuss modes of
power supply to minimize loss and destruction of vital electronic
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Participants from the Democratic Republic of Congo and Zambia
said their countries are more vulnerable to intermittent
disruptions of power to computers and other electronic equipment
during rain seasons.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains and thunderstorms are said to be among the major
causes of damage to the equipment.
</P>
<P>
A participant from the University of Zambia said that African
countries lose up to 80 percent of their electronic equipment,
worth million dollars each year in damage caused by power
interruptions.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the workshop, which opened today, are expected to
recommond the best ways of power conditioning to avoid power cuts
and prevent interruptions to protect the equipment.
</P>
<P>
African countries have over recent years invested heavily in
latest electronic equipment in various laboratories, radio
stations, hospitals and learning institutions.
</P>
<P>
Represented at the workshop are Algeria, the Democratic
Republic of Congo, Ethiopia, Kenya, Morocco, Sudan, Tanzania,
Zambia and Zimbawe. The workshop is sponsored by Zambia National
Council for Scientific Research in conjunction with the
International ATomic Energy Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Refuses further Senior Level Talks with DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday that it would not hold further senior talks between
Washington and Pyongyang because of "unacceptable demands" from
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The State Department said, however, working-level discussions
between U.S. and DPRK officials would continue so that deadlock
for four-party peace talks could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
The State Department made the announcement after the four-party
preparatory meeting broke down in New York last Friday. The four
parties include the DPRK, South Korea, the United States and
China.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James foley said: "North Korea
insists on direct linkage between the food talks and the
negotiations, and they remain inflexible" on including American
troops withdrawal from South Korea and a bilateral peace treaty
with the United States as agenda items in the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"I would be surprised if we agreed to go back to New York,
absent a firm indication on the North Korean side that they're
willing to come to agreement at a next round to permit the
four-party plenary talks to begin," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Foley said that while the United States has already sent food
aid to the DPRK and is ready to consider more, it will not link
the four-party talks with the food aid. Neither would the United
States include its troop withdrawal as an agenda item, even it is
ready to discuss the future of its 37000 troops in South Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
