<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Warned Against Hazardous Pesticides Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The UN Food and Agricultural
Organization (FAO) today warned Zambia against exporting
hazardous pesticides, Zambia News Agency (ZANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
According to a release sent to ZANA from the office of the FAO
representative in Zambia, the pesticides, which are harmful to humans,
animals and the environment should not be exported without the
agreement of the importing country.
</P>
<P>
ZANA quoted the Rome-based FAO and the UN Environment Program
(UNEP) as saying today that a prior informed consent procedure has
been established to better monitor and manage the trade of the
concerned pesticides.
</P>
<P>
The procedure can help importers to decide whether they want some
pesticides to enter their countries or not.
</P>
<P>
Extremely hazardous pesticides including organo-phosphates-
methamidophos, methyl paration, monocrotophos, and some industrial
chemicals have been added to a existing watch list of the FAO and
UNEP.
</P>
<P>
The pesticides, the two world bodies said, pose a considerable risk
to the health of many small farmers and agricultural workers because
they can not be handled safely.
</P>
<P>
Studies on the application of organophosphates have demonstrated
that during normal spraying, farmers are exposed to contamination by
absorption of residues on clothing through the skin, said ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, reports show that consumers have also been at
risk of acute poisoning following the consumption of leafy vegetables
that have been treated shortly before harvest with organophosphate
pesticides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
