<HEADLINE> Grand Slam Cup Could be Extended to Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Grand Slam Cup organisers said
in Munich on Tuesday that they were studying plans to extend the
event to women.
</P>
<P>
Tournament director Bill Dennis said the man who founded the
Grand Slam Cup, Axel Meyer-Woelden, had been keen to allow women
to participate or to create a similar tournament for women.
</P>
<P>
Meyer-Woelden, who started the tournament featuring the top
performers of all four grand slams in 1990, died last month of
liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
"In one of the last discussions we had with Axel, he told me
how keen he was to extend the formula to women," said Dennis.
"It's definitely a good idea and something we will work on."
</P>
<P>
First dismissed by many as a meaningless exhibition, the Grand
Slam Cup has become an important date on the tennis calendar. The
latest edition which started on Tuesday offers a total six million
U.S. dollars in prize money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
