<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 80 Civilians Slaughtered Near Algerian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 80 civilians, most
of them women and children, were slaughtered from Monday night to
Tuesday morning in the suburb of Algerian capital Algiers.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the victims were transported to a school, and
people at the scene described the massacre as "a butchery with
cruelty beyond imagination."
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported that troops and police had
been deployed around the area of the massacre, where several
houses were burnt down.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted survivors as saying that a small group of killers
arrived Monday night and sealed off the village with mines and
traps, before a larger group of gunmen came and began the killing.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian government denied reports of up to 200 people
being massacred. A government spokesman put the toll at 85 dead
and 67 wounded.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time in three days when civilians were
massacred in mass groups, allegedly by Islamic extremists.
</P>
<P>
The government has presented its condolences to the relatives
of the victims and vowed to fight "terrorism."
</P>
<P>
The exiled Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) leadership also
condemned the massacre and blamed the government for failing to
protect civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
