<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Launches Program for Export Promotion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh today launched an
integrated program for strengthening the country's supply capacity
of exportable goods and services with an emphasis on development
and diversification of the export sector.
</P>
<P>
The capacity building for improved governance in trade and
trade- related areas are the other priorities of the program,
Bangladesh Commerce and Industries Minister Tofail Ahmed said at
the inauguration ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The program is also aimed at integrating the Bangladesh economy
into the rapidly globalizing world economy and the international
rating system as an essential prerequisite for creating conditions
for sustainable growth and development, alleviating poverty and
generating employment.
</P>
<P>
"Export development is our top-most priority and this is the
only way through which we can integrate ourselves into the global
economic processes and eventually survive in the highly
competitive world," the minister stated.
</P>
<P>
"The objectives of poverty alleviation, rural development,
employment generation are all dependent on how best we mobilize
our resources in this direction," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's export performance over the last decade, which
registered a real average growth rate of 14 percent in the 1990s
compared to 5.5 percent in the 1980s, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Although we have been exporting 125 kinds of products to about
120 markets, 90 percent of the export receipts are occurring only
from three products -- ready-made garments, frozen food and jute
and jute goods," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Out of these products, ready-made garments alone contribute 67
percent to the country's export earnings, he said, adding that
about 50 percent of the export earnings are generated from three
market outlets -- the United States, the United Kingdom and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
"We urgently need concerted and coordinated efforts to improve
our supply capacity of the exportable goods and services and also
market access to strengthen and diversify the market base," the
minister stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
