<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Clinton's Reference in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today welcomed a
reference to it by the United States President Bill Clinton at the
United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time in years that a U.S. President refers to
Cyprus in his U.N. General Assembly address." said Cyprus
Government Spokesman Manolis Christofides today at a press
briefing.
</P>
<P>
In his address Monday to the 52nd U.N. General Assembly,
Clinton placed Cyprus among the countries where the U.N. continues
to prevent bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
"This means the Cyprus question is a priority of the U.S.
diplomacy," Christofides said, adding that Clinton's speech
coincides with "the atmosphere prevailing in the Cyprus issue and
heralds serious developments."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Clinton in his address expressed hopes that the
differences between Greece and Turkey, the respective allies of
the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities in the divided Cyprus,
will be solved.
</P>
<P>
Also hailing Clinton's speech, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos has said it is important that the U.S. president has
placed the Cyprus problem and the Greek-Turkish relationship among
the issues that have to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops on this eastern Mediterranean island and took the northern
third in the wake of a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" which is recognized only by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
