<HEADLINE> Rallies in Japan Protest New U.S.-Japan Security Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people rallied
today in Tokyo and Osaka to protest the adoption of new U.S.-Japan
security cooperation guidelines.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 people took part in the rallies in Tokyo, timed
on the day when Japan and the United States are to issue the
updated principles governing bilateral defense cooperation in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Protesters expressed anger at the new guidelines near the
Defense Agency, which was guarded by about 200 riot police.
</P>
<P>
In Osaka, about 150 citizens and labor union members gathered
at a park in Kita Ward, according to reports reaching here. They
adopted a resolution calling for a halt to the review of the 1978
security guidelines, saying it would turn Japan into a country
ready to go to war.
</P>
<P>
After a 16-month review of the 1978 security principles, Japan
and the United States would sign an agreement on the new
guidelines today. 
</P>
