<HEADLINE> WHO Regional Meeting Held to Review Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A five-day meeting of the
World Health Organisation (WHO) regional office for Africa
started here today to review the agency's activities in the past
year and prepare programs for next year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will review WHO's performance at regional and
country levels in promoting health and development on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
About 80 participants will also discuss results of an opinion
poll conducted on technical cooperation with member states as
well as a framework and draft guidelines for evaluating WHO's
activities during the 1996/97 period.
</P>
<P>
The evaluation is aimed at assessing the impact of the
organization's action on national health development and the
effectiveness of its program of cooperation with member states.
</P>
<P>
Timothy Stamps, Zimbabwe's Minister of Health and Child
Welfare, said at the opening ceremony that there was need to
involve ministries of health in evaluating collaboration between
WHO and its member countries.
</P>
<P>
"The whole objective of WHO/government collaboration is to
assist governments develop and exploit opportunities for health
improvement through national health systems based on primary
health care which will include and guide the contribution of
other partners," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged delegates to look at issues such as whether
all partners were included in individual countries' national
health policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
