<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Newspapers Required to Renew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- All 13 newspapers currently
published in Sierra Leone have been given six working days (up to
the end of September) to renew their registration if they want to
continue publication.
</P>
<P>
State radio and television reported today that the order was
made late Monday after the Commissioner of Information and
Broadcasting Sedu Turay had a meeting with Frank Kposowa,
president of the Sierra Leone Journalists Association.
</P>
<P>
Turay was quoted as saying that "the registration will be in
accordance with the 1980 Newspaper Act. We need to bring sanity
and responsibility into newspaper reporting."
</P>
<P>
"I would not take responsibility or make representation for
any publisher who draws inspiration from publishing untruths and
fertile imagination," said Kposowa.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1980 Newspaper Act, the initial fee for a
certificate of registration is 2,000 U.S. Dollars and 1,000
Dollars for annual renewal.
</P>
<P>
Almost all of the papers have not renewed their certificates
for the past three years, source from the ministry of information
said.
</P>
<P>
The act gives the commissioner the right to refuse to register
or grant renewal or suspend or cancel any registration already
granted and the aggrieved proprietor of a newspaper can appeal to
the Sierra Leone High Court within 30 days against the
commissioner's decision.
</P>
<P>
Any proprietor who violates the act risks a fine not exceeding
1,000 Dollars or a jail term not exceeding one year or both fine
and imprisonment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
