<HEADLINE> Merchant Vessels Warned not to Enter Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Colonel Max Khobe,
commander of the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) in
Sierra Leone, today said in a statement warning all merchant
vessels and their owners "to keep away from Sierra Leone due to
the sanctions and embargo now in force."
</P>
<P>
The statement was broadcast today by the clandestine FM 98.1
radio, which is supporting the return of the ousted President
Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
West African leaders at their summit in July in Abuja,
Nigeria, agreed to pressure the military government in Sierra
Leone to return power back to the civilian government through
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"The military government, some businessmen and ship's agents
are bent on violating the embargo," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement specifically "warned the captain of the merchant
ship MV SKY, the agent of the ship and the military government
that if the MV SKY or any other ship attempts to berth in
Freetown day or night, the ship will be destroyed."
</P>
<P>
The statement also warned civilians living in the vicinity of
the port to "move out of the area with immediate effect as the
port is now regarded as a military zone."
</P>
<P>
Sources told Xinhua that the MV SKY is currently anchored on
international waters outside Sierra Leone with dozens of
containers of provisions and other scarce consumer items such as
sugar which were ordered by a Lebanese merchant in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Trade Ministry officials said they would not comment on the
statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
