<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Urged to Help Develop Economy in Muslim Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari today called on the Organization of Islamic Countries
(OIC) to play a role of catalyst in promoting economic development
in Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
"The OIC has to be transformed into a dynamic organization and
bring the Muslim countries together for addressing matters of
mutual concern," Leghari said while inaugurating a three-day
conference on "the Muslim Ummah in the next century" here.
</P>
<P>
Institutions like the Islamic Development Bank providing help
for cooperation among the Muslim countries should be strengthened,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Muslim countries should develop their economies to be able to
respond to the challenges presented by a fast-changing world, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for greater integration of the Muslim economies
to maximize the advantages of mutual trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Islamic financial institutions, he said, should not only be
strengthened but charged with the task of finding solutions to the
financial problems being faced by the Islamic world, Leghari said.
</P>
<P>
The president said the Muslim countries should not remain
dependent on scientific and technological assistance from others.
</P>
<P>
"Continued dependence on imported technology cannot foster
autarky nor create a conducive environment for regeneration of
real and sustained interest in the development of a scientific
approach," he said.
</P>
<P>
Leghari noted that efforts should be made to foster greater
unity within the Muslim Ummah to overcome differences and
divisions.
</P>
<P>
"We must collectively defend those Islamic people who are
victims of aggression, or are suffering under foreign occupation
and oppression," he said. "We should stand united against the
denial of the inalienable right to self-determination."  
</P>
</TEXT>
