<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Postpones Projects for Economic Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
decided to postpone or review 214 government projects, state-owned
enterprises and private companies in a bid to realize economic
stability following the rupiah's depreciation against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
A presidential decree to the effect was issued last Saturday
and the projects to be affected are worth 178.789 trillion rupiah
(about 62 billion U.S. dollars), Minister/State Secretary
Moerdiono said when announcing the decree here today.
</P>
<P>
"The government has set up a team which will continue to
evaluate (the projects), and we will reevaluate the projects if
the situation enables (us to do so)," Moerdiono said.
</P>
<P>
On September 16, the Indonesian government announced the plan
to postpone and review some government and private projects in
order to reduce state budget deficit as a result of the rupiah
depreciation since July this year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the projects to be postponed are in mining, energy, oil
and transportation fields and some others have a high import
content.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rupiah, like other regional currencies, has come
under fierce speculative attack following the de facto devaluation
of the Thai baht and the Philippine peso in July. The rupiah has
fallen about 25 percent since January this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
