<HEADLINE> China's Vice Premier Says Reforms and Opening Up Will Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing,
meeting today with Peter Cazalet, president of the China-Britain
Trade Group, and a delegation led by Iwao Isomura, president of
the Tokai Japan-China Trade Center today, said that China will be
more active in its reform and opening up, now that Deng Xiaoping's
theory has been recognized as the Party's guiding ideology.
</P>
<P>
Li said that general secretary Jiang Zemin's report at the
Party's 15th National Congress is a political declaration and
action program and that establishing Deng's theory as the Party's
guideline was the most important issue of the Congress.
</P>
<P>
He said that China will continue to implement its policy of
"one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people governing Hong
Kong" with a high-degree of autonomy in Hong Kong to maintain the
region's prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Li discussed China's enterprise and fiance system reforms and
encouraged the two visiting groups to expand co-operation with
China to contribute more to Sino-British and Sino-Japanese
economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
In welcoming the Japanese group, the Tokai Area Economic World
Mission to China, Li noted that both sides are celebrating the
25th anniversary of the normalization of diplomatic relations and
said that government and non-government contacts between the two
countries this year have promoted bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Both sides should keep history in mind, he said, and teach the
younger generation to cherish the friendship so as to pass
friendly relations on from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
Cazalet said that, in Hong Kong, his first stop of this visit,
people are full of confidence about their future. In Britain, as
well, people have restored confidence in investment in and trade
co-operation with China, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will continue to serve as a bridge between Britain
and China instead of standing in the way, he noted. 
</P>
