<HEADLINE> Forest Expect Tougher UEFA Action Against Anderlecht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Nottingham Forest on Tuesday
said that UEFA should impose tougher penalties on Anderlecht for
bribing referees in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Belgium's biggest club will not be allowed to play in the next
European competition for which it qualifies, UEFA announced on
Monday, after UEFA said it bribed officials in 1983 and 1984, the
year Anderlecht beat Forest to reach the UEFA Cup final.
</P>
<P>
Forest spokesman Larry Lloyd said European soccer's governing
body had been soft on Anderlecht.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that Anderlecht undermined the whole moral and
ethical base of football," Lloyd said in a statement. "Nottingham
Forest are of the opinion that UEFA have not gone far enough in
their punishment of Anderlecht."
</P>
<P>
Anderlecht recently admitted having paid one million francs
(27,000 U.S. dollars) as a "loan" to the Spanish referee in the
second leg of the 1984 Cup semifinal which they won 3-0. Forest
had a goal controversially disallowed.
</P>
<P>
Last week first division Forest said it would seek compensation
for their former players involved in the 1984 campaign as well as
suing Anderlecht for 1.5 million pounds (2.4 million U.S. dollars)
in lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the players who played in that game have joined forces
with the club in agreeing to seek further action," Lloyd said.
</P>
<P>
"Nottingham Forest and the players involved will be guided by
legal advice from Brussels, " he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
