<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> English Transfer System Faces Shake-up in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- England's premier league plans
to have a new transfer system in July, but the scheme faces
opposition from smaller soccer clubs.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system, which promotes "player power" in the
aftermath of the Bosman ruling, a player over 24 who reached the
end of his contract would be able to move clubs without a transfer
fee.
</P>
<P>
These players would, however, expect to attract a sizeable
signing-on fee and negotiate huge salaries.
</P>
<P>
Mike Lee, spokesman for the premier league, said on Tuesday it
wanted this new system to start from July 1, 1998, during the
soccer close season. It has the support of the players' "trade
union", the Professional Footballers' Association (PFA).
</P>
<P>
But he said the premier league had not reached agreement with
the Football League, representing the interests of clubs in lower
divisions.
</P>
<P>
"They understand the need for reform but they are seeking a
transitional period," Lee said. "We believe that this season was
the transitional period and we now need a clean and simple break."
</P>
<P>
He said the new system would not affect the in-contract system
from which most clubs in the lower leagues derive their transfer
income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
