<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Signs Missiles Contract with Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain has signed a
contract with Kuwait for the supply of anti-ship missiles to
be mounted on patrol boats of the Kuwaiti naval forces, the
visiting British Defense Secretary George Robertson announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
Robertson said through a press release of the British Embassy
in Kuwait that "this contract is the latest to be placed under
government to government arrangements for the (supply of )
defense equipment which were signed after the Gulf War."
</P>
<P>
He said that the British Ministry of Defense has signed a
contract with the Kuwaiti government, under which Britain is to
sell Matra British Aerospace Dynamics Sea Skua anti-ship missiles
to this gulf country.
</P>
<P>
Previous purchases have been the GKN warrior infantry
fighting vehicles and short Starbust anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
He said "this is excellent news, Sea Skua missile was a major
factor in winning the naval battle during the liberation of
Kuwait and will be a great enhancement to Kuwait's ability to
deter and combat any future aggression."
</P>
<P>
However, the minister did not disclose the value of the
contract and when the missiles are expected to be delivered.
</P>
<P>
Robertson arrived in Kuwait Monday on a three-day official
visit to the Gulf state during which he held talks with
Kuwaiti leaders on boosting military relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Robertson's visit is within a Gulf tour which already took him
to Oman and will also take him to the United Arab Emirates. It is
the first visit by a British defense minister to the sensitive
Gulf region since the new Labor government took office in Britain
in May this year.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Robertson met with Kuwaiti leaders
and visited a British ship taking part in the commission of
enforcement of international sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Robertson told a limited pool of local reporters yesterday
that he held "detailed discussions" with senior Kuwaiti
officials raising security issues and several potential defense
deals for British contractors.
</P>
<P>
"We talked about a number of procurement orders that are
still ongoing," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
The British new Labor government reassured Kuwait in May
right after it assumed power that it would continue the
policy undertaken by the previous administration which is aimed
at ensuring Kuwait's stability and security.
</P>
<P>
The two countries reiterated their determination to strengthen
their defense cooperation in all fields in London last
February during a visit by Kuwaiti Defense Minister Sheik
Salem Sabah Al-Salem Al-Sabah to Britain.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Britain signed a defense cooperation agreement in
1992 following the 1991 Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
