<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Ministry on Sino-US Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman
Shen Guofang said today that, in the new situation in the world,
China and the United States should forge a new bilateral
relationship oriented toward the 21st century, one that focuses on
mutual benefit and co-operation and is not aimed at a third
country.
</P>
<P>
Shen told a press conference in Beijing this afternoon that,
because China is the biggest developing country and the US the
biggest developed one, and because both are permanent members of
the UN Security Council, a sound and good Sino-US relationship is
"very important". The two countries share common understanding on
many regional and international issues, and have had good and
effective cooperation on some issues.
</P>
<P>
"We should be aware of the fact that there is more in common
than difference between the two sides," he said, adding that
difference and different points of view on some questions can be
settled or reduced through dialogue and consultation and are not
really that important.
</P>
<P>
China places great emphasis on Sino-US relations, he said, and
in recent months, bilateral relations have continued to improve
and develop, and China is looking forward to further development
of bilateral ties after Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to
the US scheduled for this fall.
</P>
<P>
He said that improved Sino-US relations are good for the two
countries, and for regional and international peace and stability
as well.
</P>
<P>
In reference to the Taiwan question, he said that the US should
not interfere in China's internal affairs, but that it can do
something on this issue, that is, it should not sell large amounts
of advanced weapons to Taiwan and should not encourage in any form
 any activity aimed at creating "two Chinas" or "one China, one
Taiwan".
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan question is a very important issue in Sino-US
relations, he noted, and if the US can handle this issue in
accordance with the three joint communiques, it will help relax
relations across the Taiwan Straits and will help advance the
process of China's peaceful reunification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
