<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Expects New Forest Code to Protect Loggers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Some 30 experts from 10 major
forest countries today began a week-long discussion about a new
Code of Practice on Safety and Health in Forest Work which the
International Labor Organization (ILO) expects to protect loggers
and the environment.
</P>
<P>
Forest work is an occupation practiced by some three million
people and considered as one of the most hazardous in the world,
ILO said in a press release here today.
</P>
<P>
Every year, thousands of forest workers die or are injured in
forest work due to unsafe practices and the danger of working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the press release said that unsafe forestry has an
environmental impact, causing more damage than necessary to
remaining timber crops.
</P>
<P>
Experts from Brazil, Canada, Chile, the Czech Republic, Gabon,
Malaysia, New Zealand, South Africa, Sweden, and the United States
will meet at ILO headquarters here on September 23-30 to discuss
the new code of practice which draws on international experience
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The new code outlines a legal and institutional framework for
safety in forestry through which governments, employers, workers,
forest owners, labor inspectors, machine manufacturers and others
have specific roles to play.
</P>
<P>
It also suggests a training system which will ensure access by
the entire workforce and lead to demonstrated and certified levels
of skill.
</P>
<P>
The new code covers all types of forest workers, including
groups with higher than average accident frequencies like
contractors, self-employed and forest farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
