<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Military Leader Willing to Negotiate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Senior foreign ministry
officials in Sierra Leone told Xinhua today that military leader
Major Johnny Paul Koroma "is willing to negotiate a peaceful
solution" to the current political impasse in the west African
state.
</P>
<P>
One official quoted a letter to the United Nations Security
Council by Koroma four days ago, saying the Sierra Leone leader
"wants to meet ousted President Tejan Kabbah and rebel leader
Foday Sankoh for talks."
</P>
<P>
"Major Koroma expressed gratitude for the welcome step taken
by the UN to appoint Uganda-born Francis Okelo as special envoy
to Sierra Leone to study the problem at first hand," said the
official.
</P>
<P>
"This is what the people of Sierra Leone have been asking for
over the past few months and we sincerely believe that this is a
move the international community should have taken in the first
place," according to the letter.
</P>
<P>
"Despite everything we have done to restrain the anger of our
people after the brutal massacre by the Nigerian component of
ECOMOG (west African peace-keeping force) on the 3rd and 4th of
September perpetrating on our innocent citizenry, despite all the
efforts that we have made to call on the rest of the world to
stop Nigerians from committing acts of aggression without the
mandate of the Security Council, despite the blood and tears of
our babies, our mothers, our sisters and our old people, Nigeria
continues to kill us with impunity and disregard for human and
international decency," the letter added.
</P>
<P>
It went on saying that "the people of Sierra Leone may be poor
and insignificant but according to the UN Charter, we are still
members of the human race. The UN and the world should not
require our battered and maimed bodies and our torn limbs to
prove it."
</P>
<P>
"We as a ruling council are nonetheless willing to enter into
talks with anyone for the sake of our people. We are ready to
talk at the level at ECOWAS (the Economic Community of West
African States). We are ready to talk at the level of the United
Nations and I am personally ready to enter into tripartite
negotiations with Mr. Ahmad Tejan Kabbah and Corporal Foday
Sankoh," Koroma concluded in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here said Koroma's letter marked the
latest twist to finding a workable solution to the constitutional
stalemate after the May 25 military coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
