<HEADLINE> China's Poverty-Eradication Success Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the UN World
Food Program (WFP) and other agencies today spoke highly of
China's poverty-elimination efforts at a seminar in the program's
Beijing Office.
</P>
<P>
They said they agree that China has set a good example for
other developing countries to follow in co-operating with
international organizations in assisting poor people.
</P>
<P>
Gao Hongbin, an official from the State Council Leading Group
for Poverty Alleviation and Development, said that China has
scored achievements in its poverty-elimination efforts and that
the number of rural people below the poverty line dropped from 250
million in 1979 to 58 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, he told the participants, China now encounters
enormous difficulties in the drive because the remaining 58
million live in remote, rocky mountainous areas and in areas
inhabited by ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
Because of extremely harsh natural conditions in these areas,
he noted, the international community should continue to help
China in its anti-poverty campaign.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese government spent 15.3 billion yuan on
poverty relief in 1996 alone.
</P>
<P>
Present at the seminar were a delegation from Rome's WFP
headquarters. Members of the delegation are scheduled to visit
Qinghai and Gansu provinces where there are WFP-aided agricultural
development projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
