<HEADLINE> Philippine Court Rejects Charter Change Petition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of the
Philippines today rejected a petition of the People's Initiative
for Reform, Modernization and Action (PIRMA) for a people's
initiative to amend the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal unanimously voted 13-0, junking the PIRMA petition
for charter changes to lift term limits of the president and other
elected officials.
</P>
<P>
The junking of the petition came two days after President Fidel
Ramos categorically declared that charter changes should be made
after the May 1998 elections and he will not run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's constitution, the president serves a single
six-year term and is not allowed to run for a second term.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos, who was inaugurated on June 30, 1992, thus
cannot run for re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
After the supreme court rejected the PIRMA's petition,
Executive Secretary Ruben Torres urged the group to abide by the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
"I think the supreme court has already decided on their case so
they should abide by that decision," Torres said.
</P>
<P>
Torres said Ramos has proposed that charter changes should
take place after next year's national election and delegates to a
constitutional convention (ConCon) should be elected
simultaneously with the May 1998 polls.
</P>
<P>
"I think the call of the president for ConCon should be the
right move to take and that will be after 1998," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president suggested that charter changes be made by the way
of a constitutional convention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
