<HEADLINE> Iraq Receives 90 Percent of Food Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has received 90 percent
of the contracted foodstuff within the first phase of an
oil-for-food deal, U.N. humanitarian affairs coordinator in Iraq,
Dennis Haleidy, announced here today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Haleidy said 2 million tonnes of the
food articles including vegetable oil, sugar and rice have arrived
since the deal came into force last December.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the remaining amount of the food
articles will reach Iraq within the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
Haleidy pointed out that the U.N. Sanctions Committee has been
slow in approving the contracts Iraq concluded with foreign
companies, subsequently delaying the arrival of food supply.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the food supply can reach Iraq more
promptly in the second stage of the oil-for-food deal beginning in
June.
</P>
<P>
Haleidy, who is an Irish, has been the U.N. humanitarian
affairs coordinator in Iraq since early this month.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has called on the U.N. Sanctions Committee to hurry up in
approving its contracts for purchasing food articles and medicines
and to set a time ceiling for Iraq to receive them.
</P>
<P>
Iraq struck an oil-for-food deal with the U.N. in May 1996
which allowed Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil
over a six-month period to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian goods. The deal was renewed in June this year.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi people have been suffering from the six-year-old
U.N. sanctions imposed following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
