<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Amount of Defaulted Bills Sharply Up in S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The daily average amount of
defaulted bills in South Korean banks marked a hefty 13-fold
increase from that of seven years ago, in a chain-reaction to
bankruptcies of major corporate failures, including Hanbo and
Sammi groups.
</P>
<P>
The amount of the first half of this year reached 70.2 billion
won (7.8 million U.S dollars), more than 13 times over the 5.4
billion won (6 million dollars) recorded in 1990, said the Bank of
Korea.
</P>
<P>
The figure, which had steadily increased from 12.6 billion won
(1.4 million dollars) to 43.9 billion won (4.8 million dollars) in
1995, showed a temporary decline to 41.9 billion won (4.7 million
dollars) last year, before surging to a record high this year, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The total number of bouncing checks for the first six months of
this year was 566,700, worth about 10.18 trillion won (11 billion
dollars). The average amount per defaulted bill was 18 million won
(20,000 dollars), up 309 percent from 4.4 million won (4,800
dollars) recorded in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The average amount of defaulted bills was also on a steady rise
from 8.1 million won (9,000 dollars) in 1991 to 12.5 million won
(14,000 dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The rate of defaulted bills also rose from 0.04 percent in 1990
to 0.06 percent in 1991 and hit 0.20 percent in 1995. Last year,
it dropped to 0.17 percent but rebounded to 0.29 percent in the
first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The default rate of personal checks was 2.31 percent, while
those of promissory notes and corporate checks stood at 0.45
percent and 0.18 percent, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
