<HEADLINE> IMF Official Calls for Imposing Monetary Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Stanley Fischer, first
deputy manager director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
today urged Thailand and other member-countries to impose monetary
control and improve financial structure for avoiding financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center focusing on the recent financial crisis in
Thailand, Fischer said the recent financial turmoil in Thailand
showed the consequences of a combination of a weak financial
system and inadequate macroeconomic policies.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, he said, the IMF views the widespread
incidence of major banking failures throughout the world as of
extreme importance for its surveillance of its members'
macroeconomic policies.
</P>
<P>
Fischer also said Thailand should improve its financial system
and monetary conditions before the deadline fixed for mid-October
in accordance with the IMF's bailout program.
</P>
<P>
In August, Thailand was forced to turn to the IMF for arranging
a loan of 17.2 billion U.S. dollars after the country's financial
system went into a tailspin, causing financial disturbances in the
Southeast Asian region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Prison Established in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A maximum security
prison for South Africa's most violent criminals was officially
opened in Pretoria on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Inmates at the new closed maximum security unit (CMSU) would
not be allowed to smoke, shave or talks to one another, and would
be locked in their solitary cells for 23 hours a day, local media
today quoted Minister of Correctional Service Sipo Mzimela as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the new concept was a forerunner to envisaged super
maximum prisons, the first of which was expected to be launched
in the country in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The CMSU would house murders, rapists, escaped inmates, gang
leaders, prisoners with violent records, and those found guilty
of murdering fellow inmates, prison staff and police members.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners in the unit would be allowed only the minimum human
rights as enshrined in the constitution, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
All the prisoners' meals would be served in their cells, to be
eaten with plastic utensils, and they would at no stage be
allowed to leave their cells without cuffs.
</P>
<P>
Mzimela said the CMSU had several high-tech security features,
including stun belt, and the cuffing of the inmate's hands to his
waist which should be needed when the inmates have to leave the
prison to go to court or a hospital, guarded by two security
staff.
</P>
<P>
An electronic device is attached to the stun belt which can be
activated by remote control to administer a 50,000 volt shock,
rendering the inmate paralyzed, but not dead.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's crime rate is one of the highest in the world.
The government is taking a number of steps to enhance the police
and security systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0138 </DOCNO>
