<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Leather Industry Has Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's leather industry
could become one of the country's major foreign exchange earners
if it is properly harnessed, the Export Board of Zambia (EBZ) has
said.
</P>
<P>
Currently the sector is producing intermediary products for
export and ready-made items to meet local demand, according to
the latest EBZ Export Review available here today.
</P>
<P>
The EBZ said that the industry continued to grow in terms of
export last year by a notable seven percent and contributed a
total of 2.093 million U.S. Dollars to the total earnings of
Zambia's non-traditional exports of 310 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Italy is the largest market with a total value of 1.4 million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Crust leather accounted for a total 128,000 Dollars, all of
which went to South Africa while the remaining finished leather
was exported to Malawi, Zimbabwe and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
However, the sector has been facing varied problems, such as
inadequate supply of raw materials that has led to tanneries not
operating at full capacity with big producers operating at around
50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other problems include the high tariffs in potentially
lucrative markets such as South Africa which is inhibiting access
on a competitive basis.
</P>
<P>
South Africa slaps a 35 percent import tariff on Zambia's
leather products as opposed to free access which members of the
Southern African Customs Union enjoy.
</P>
<P>
The EBZ said that Zambia as a whole stands to benefit from an
increase in export if only a vigorous pursuit on the issue of
bilateral trade agreements with neighboring countries mounted.
</P>
<P>
The EBZ also said Zambia's crocodile skin continued to show
great potential, earning the country 320,000 Dollars from export
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
