<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bihar State Leads in India's Leprosy Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Notwithstanding the Indian
government's program to eradicate leprosy by the turn of the
century, 50,000 new cases had been reported in the country's
eastern state of Bihar by March this year, a state government
survey showed.
</P>
<P>
Bihar leads the country in prevalence and spread of the disease
with an estimated 500,000 patients, according to the survey, whose
results were published today.
</P>
<P>
Though the spread rate came down from five per thousand in 1995
to two per thousand last year, it was still higher than the
national average of 0.9 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
Patna, capital of Bihar State, as well as Nawada, Purnea and
Rohtas have been identified as the worst-affected areas, where
union government-sponsored multi-drug therapy has been introduced
to check it, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The state government has decided to set up special committees
to identify fresh cases, particularly in villages, and launch a
special drive to eradicate the disease, a state spokesman said
today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
