<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small is Beautiful for Role of Govt: WB Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Government should play a
small and consolidated role, leaving the market ample room in
economic life, according to panelists at a World Bank seminar here
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the seminar on "The Role of the State", Anatoly
Chubais, first deputy prime minister of Russia, mentioned two
principles: "First, there should be as less state role as
possible; second, in the field that needs a role of government,
the role should be as strong as possible."
</P>
<P>
Chubais, also minister of finance of the Russian Federation,
said that since 1991 the Russian government has taken steps to
rebuild its role in a market economy in transition.
</P>
<P>
The state has played a macroeconomic role, said that the
official, by curbing inflation from ten percent per month several
years before to ten percent per year now, stabilizing the exchange
rate between the Rupee and the greenback, and controlling
government finance and budget.
</P>
<P>
Privatization is in progress as the government is withdrawing
from the economy, according to Chubais. He stressed that the
government role is strengthened in such fields as providing a
social safety net, attacking corruption and ensuring law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Another speaker at the seminar, Trevor Manuel, minister of
finance of South Africa, listed some fundamental roles government
should play, including establishing a foundation of law,
maintaining macro-economic stability, providing basic
infrastructure and protecting the most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
In his presentation, Luiz Carlos Bresser Pereira, minster of
Federal Administration and State Reform of Brazil, proposed to
"set the limits for the sphere of action of the state".
</P>
<P>
He said that civil service should be the exclusive and core
activities of the state. The social and scientific services should
be shifted from the control of bureaucratic bodies to the hand of
the non-profit organizations, while production of goods and
services should be privatized to let market play its role,
according to the Brazilian official.
</P>
<P>
Today's discussion was among a series of four-day seminars
organized by the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) prior to and during their joint annual meetings, which
opened here today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
