<HEADLINE> HK Dollar, Thai Baht Not in Same Basket: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today ruled out any possibility of major impact on the
Hong Kong dollar by the recent currency turmoil in Southeast Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
In view of different situation in capital accounts of Hong Kong
and Thailand, the HK dollar and the Thai Baht are not in the same
"basket of currencies", IMF First Deputy Managing Director Stanley
Fischer said at a press conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is an international financial center and its economy
has unique advantages, so the HK dollar is entirely a single
currency, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
"It's theoretically possible but extremely difficult to tie
them to a basket of currencies," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So given the role of Hong Kong as a financial center, it's a
very different economy with different level of development from
Thailand," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted that it is crucial to strengthen
government surveillance over the banking sector to reduce currency
risks. The IMF believes that "much importance" should be placed
on surveillance, he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the IMF warned Thai authorities against
possible crisis last April. If proper measures were taken then,
the prices paid now to deal with the problem would have been much
less, he added.
</P>
<P>
While describing the current devaluation of the Thai Baht as
"not a massive overreaction" by the market, he expressed
confidence that the problem can be dealt with eventually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
