<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan, Belarus to Promote Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev and his Belarussian counterpart Alexander Lukashenko
vowed to improve bilateral relations in a joint declaration issued
here today.
</P>
<P>
In the Kazakh-Belarussian Joint Declaration, the two presidents
agreed the traditional friendship among the former Soviet
republics would be kept on bases of mutual respect, equality and
mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
They said that strengthened integration would be helpful to the
development of the former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev told reporters that the Kazakh-Belarussian bilateral
trade has dropped in the past two years due to some problems in
transportation and taxation policies.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries would make joint efforts to promote
the cooperation within the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS).
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko, who arrived here Monday for a three-day visit to
Kazakhstan, said that Belarus and Kazakhstan have great potential
in economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of the Customs Union formed by
Russia, Kazakhstan, Belarus and Kyrgyzstan in improving trade
development in the four countries.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the two governments also signed accords on
free trade, cooperation in air transportation, mutual protection
for labor rights of each other's citizens in the other country,
mutual militarized supervision over import and export of military
supplies, and youth policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
