<HEADLINE> 65000 HIV Infections Reported in Western Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Organization's (WHO) Western Pacific Conference was told today in
Sydney that as of August this year, 65,000 HIV infections had been
reported in the Western Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
But it was estimated 300,000 people had the disease in the
region, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Of the 65,000 cases 70 percent were attributed to sexual
transmissions and 30 percent to injecting drug use.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the region where increasing HIV epidemics have
been recorded included Cambodia, Papua New Guinea, China, Malaysia
and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The conference was told low levels of HIV transmission were
recorded in Japan, Pacific island nations, the Philippines and the
Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Declining HIV epidemics were recorded in Australia and New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
WHO estimates by the year 2000, 700,000 in the region will be
infected by HIV.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Peter Piot of the United Nation's HIV/AIDS Program said the
only way the problem (HIV infection) will be beaten is if a
vaccine is discovered.
</P>
<P>
"If we ever want to eradicate AIDS we will have to have a
vaccine," he said.
</P>
<P>
He praised Australia's HIV/AIDS reduction schemes, such as the
controversial needle exchange program.
</P>
<P>
Although not willing to become involved in the public debate on
the program, Piot said Australia's AIDS strategies were now being
modeled by "conservative" countries such as China, Nepal and
Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
