<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close higher with Shifting Sentiment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
has finished slightly higher today after a volatile day of trading
based on shifting sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended up 12 points at 2776.9,
eclipsing yesterday's record closing high, with brokers noting
resources remained heavy while buyers sought industrial buying
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
One stock that has attracted strong interest today is Qantas,
Australia's largest airline, whose shares finished 13 cents down
at 2.80 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some brokers suggested the fall could be attributed to an
article in an aviation trade magazine which said Qantas faces
declining profitability in the face of flat revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
News Corp shares also performed well, up 19 cents to 6.80
Australian dollars, while its preferred shares improved 16 cents
to 5.80 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, Westpac shares rose 14 cents to 9.04
Australian dollars, with brokers attributing the rise to the
approaching share buyback and buyers bringing the stock up to the
level of its banking rivals.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank (NAB) has closed steady at 22.25
Australian dollars, ceding its position as Australia's largest
company by market capitalization to resources giant BHP after just
one day at the top.
</P>
<P>
BHP has reclaimed its position as Australia's biggest company
after its shares rose 11 cents to 15.89 Australian dollars, taking
its capitalization to 32.08 billion Australian dollars (23.09
billion U.S. dollars) compared to NAB's 31.52 billion Australian
dollars (22.69 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the poor outlook for commodities has continued to
affect the major resource stocks, with mining company WMC falling
seven cents to 6.14 Australian dollars and Rio Tinto finishing
down 14 cents to 20.98 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the gold sector, stock prices have closed generally down
with the bullion price trading at 320.75 U.S. dollars per ounce
compared to yesterday's close of 320.90 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 4.1 points higher at 1337.8
while the all industrials index has finished 21.7 points higher at
4600.7.
</P>
<P>
Turnover for the day has been strong, with 408.08 million
shares traded at a value of 1.49 billion Australian dollars (1.07
billion U.S. dollars), with rises outnumbering falls 673 to 626.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
