<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Tourism Ministerial Meeting Opens in Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The two-day tourism
ministerial meeting of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) opened here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga, SAARC Secretary
General Naeem Hasan and tourism ministers from the seven SAARC
member states attended the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga called the meeting "a historic event" in
the region's development.
</P>
<P>
She said the tourist industry has been the major engine of
progress for the developed countries as well as the developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
"The South Asian nations have some of the most beautiful
natural resorts in the world and deserve to receive more tourist
arrivals," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Tourism Minister Dharmasiri Senanayake in his
address urged the ministers to adopt necessary measures to speed
up the development of the region's tourism.
</P>
<P>
He said the total SAARC region only receives less than one
percent of the international tourist arrivals in the world.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, SAARC Secretary General Naeem Hasan said: "We
need to remind ourselves that promotion of tourism is not only
important from the economic point of view, but is also deeply
important to projecting and promoting images of our countries to
the outside world."
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, it's necessary to develop intra-regional tourism
within the SAARC countries in order to promote people to people
contacts, which can make important contribution to the development
of the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
Several policy decisions relating to tourism in the region are
expected to be taken up for discussion in the meeting. The last
tourism ministers meeting was held in 1969.
</P>
<P>
On the agenda are the possibilities of simplifying visa-related
procedures and documentation for nationals of SAARC countries,
establishing direct air links between the seven capitals and
introducing special air fares within the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will also explore the possibility of the
convertibility of SAARC currencies within the region and the
simplification of customs formalities to and from SAARC nations.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, established in December 1985, groups India, Sri Lanka,
Nepal, the Maldives, Bhutan, Pakistan and Bangladesh and has a
total population of 1.2 billion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
