<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French government has launched partial privatization of
the state telecommunication monopoly France Telecom by putting 20
percent of its stocks into the market, which is the first time for
a French public enterprise to sell its shares in stock
exchange. The government wishes to obtain 36 billion francs (6
billion U.S. dollars) from the operation, and use the money to
finance international development of the group at a time when
France opens its telecommunication market to competition by
January 1998.
</P>
<P>
-- The Solidarity trade union of Poland and the electoral
alliance it had formed by gathering around it 38 rightwing parties
was confirmed to be the first political force of Poland on Monday,
and is now intending to form a coalition government with the central
parties. The result of legislative elections on Sunday was a frank
victory for the right, which was eliminated from institutions in the
1993 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The major financial take-overs in Europe have doped the stock
exchange in Paris and other European financial centers, with the CAC
40 index of the Paris Bourse attaining 3,017.45 points on Monday.
The markets have been doped by three other factors since August: a
strong dollar, a euphoric Wall Street and relaxed banking interest
rates. The recent take-over bids, such as the Casino supermarket
chain by Promodes, the Salomon sports commodities group by Adidas,
had made the financial operations in the bourse wild.
</P>
<P>
-- The European space rocket Ariane will send its 100th
satellite, an American telecommunications Intelsat 803 satellite,
tonight from Kourou, the French Guiana, since it began sending
satellites in December 1979. These 18 years have proved the
reliability of European space technology and brought about
commercial success for the European Space Agency, which now runs 60
percent of the world market of satellite-launching. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
