<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Interest Rates Drop to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Optimism about continuing
low inflation in Sweden and positive news from the United States
made Sweden to lower its interest rates on Monday to its lowest
level in years, local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The yield on ten-year bonds fell to a record low of 6.25
percent Monday, surprising many financial analysts, most of whom
have been preaching for months that the bond market was levelling.
</P>
<P>
However, after a turbulent spring, interest rates defied
forecasters by starting to fall. Compared to their high of 7.47
percent at the end of March, long-dated bonds fell by over 150
basic points to Monday's 6.25 percent, the lowest rate since early
1987.
</P>
<P>
The drop in interest rates was mainly driven by rising
expectations that today's report from the Sweden's central bank
will confirm the low inflation trend as well as the decline in the
yields on U.S. 30-year T-bonds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
