<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Countries Urged to Reduce Uncertainty in World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The developed countries
must act as soon as possible to reduce uncertainty and
destabilizing factors in the world economy, a senior Chinese
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the joint Annual Meetings of the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) which opened here today, Chinese
Finance Minister Liu Zhongli said that although the world economy
situations continued to be encouraging, a wide range of risks and
fragility's persist in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
"The international financial market has experienced some
unrest," he said. "Especially disturbing is that developed
countries continue to shirk their international obligations --
official development assistance as a share of their gross national
product has dropped to the lowest level in 50 years."
</P>
<P>
These problems, if not addressed in a timely and effective
manner, will not only dampen the economic future of developing
countries, but also undermine the sustainability of the global
economic growth, he added.
</P>
<P>
Noting the World Bank's contribution in promoting the
development of developing countries, Liu hoped the Bank to make
full use of its comparative advantages and continue to focus on
transferring resources to developing countries, alleviating
poverty and promoting sustainable development as its core
operations.
</P>
<P>
He said China supports the Multilateral Investment Guarantee
Agency to increase its underwriting capacity, and is willing to
take its share of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
As for the implementation of the debt relief initiative for the
highly indebted poor countries, Liu urged creditors, especially
the Paris Club members, to honor their commitments in a timely
manner to benefit eligible countries as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Liu stressed that the responsibility of fighting corruption
rests solely with sovereign governments.
</P>
<P>
"The two institutions should act in strict accordance with
their respective mandates, limit their anti-corruption activities
to the economic aspects, and ensure uniformity of treatment of
all members based on objective criteria," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
China supports the extension of the IMF's jurisdiction to
capital account and endorses its inclusion in the IMF's purpose,
Liu said.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed those members with immature conditions
should be allowed to proceed toward capital account convertibility
in an orderly and healthy manner based on their real situations.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0163 </DOCNO>
