<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Employment Index Drops to Years' Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Amid a protracted business
slowdown, the number of retiring employees in South Korea has
topped that of new employees in the past two years and the gap is
getting wider, the National Statistical Office (NSO) said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the NSO report based on a Labor Ministry tally,
the ratio of new employees to retiring employees in the
manufacturing sector stood at 84.0 percent in July, marking the
lowest level since January 1993, when the corresponding figure was
79.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
July's ratio of 84 percent was also the lowest figure since
July of 1980, when the ratio was 82.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ratio in the manufacturing sector has remained below the
100-percent level since September of 1995. The last time it stayed
above 100 percent was in August 1995 with 100.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The entrants-retirees ratio in the job market stayed at around
90 percent throughout last year but fell to 84.3 percent in June
this year.
</P>
<P>
NSO officials said the ongoing decline of the ratio, which
often serves as a leading indicator of economy, shows that the
economy is likely to bottom out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hubei Sets up Protection Zone for Fossilized Dinosaur Eggs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hubei Province
has built a 15,000-square meter protection zone for the world's
most well-preserved groups of fossilized dinosaur eggs discovered
in its Yunxian County.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Yang Jialu, a well-known paleontologist from China's
Geological University, said the eggs date back more than 65
million years.
</P>
<P>
He added that the well-preserved fossilized eggs will have high
value in the study on prehistoric geography, the earth's natural
disasters, the origin of life, the reasons for the extinction of
dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
The location where local paleontologists spotted the fossilized
dinosaur eggs in March 1995 covers a total area of 450,000 square
meters. More than 1,300 of the eggs were visible above-ground.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the new egg discovery, another group of fossilized
eggs had been unearthed in Xixia County in Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
The local government has announced that anyone who digs up or
sells the eggs will be punished, and that the related departments
will extend the area of the zone to better protect the eggs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 46 Killed in Cattle Rustling Near Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from
Saturday's raids in western Kenyas' Lokiriama and Lorengipi
areas, about six kilometers from the border with Uganda, has
risen to 46, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Kenyan police confirmed that 31 people including
nine raiders were killed in the cattle rustling. The raiders,
believed to be Pokot and Tepes from Uganda, took away hundreds of
domestic animals.
</P>
<P>
Another 12 bodies belong to the Pokot and Tepes from Uganda
were found in the Lorengipi area, said the latest reports, adding
the Kenyan police so far have recovered more than 1,000 goats,
400 donkeys and 400 camels.
</P>
<P>
However, tension remained high on the entire Turkana and West
Pokot border as Turkana pastoralists braced for more attacks.
Primary schools in both Lorengipi and Lokiriama have been closed
down.
</P>
<P>
In another attack on Friday, three people were killed and two
others seriously injured when armed raiders, believed to be from
East Baringo and the Masoul area of West Pokot, raided Turkana.
</P>
<P>
Police sources were quoted as saying that more than 1,000
raiders have crossed the border into Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Turkana District Commissioner Reuben Rotich has confirmed the
attacks, adding that the security personnel were still on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 people have died in clashes between security
personnel and cattle rustlers in Turkana and Pokot district over
the past three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
