<HEADLINE> Chinese Outstanding Neurosurgery Expert Awarded HLHL Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A noted Chinese neurosurgeon
was presented with the Ho Leung Ho Lee (HLHL) Prize, China's
largest non-government award for scientific development, in Hong
Kong today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhongcheng, director of the Beijing Neurosurgery Research
Institute, is one of the two winners of this year's HLHL Science and
Technology Achievement Prize. He will receive one million HK
dollars (130,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 73-year-old scientist, an academician of the Chinese
Academy of Engineering, is regarded as the pioneer of neurosurgery
in China.
</P>
<P>
The other winner is Qian Weichang, a prestigious mathematician
and physician of China, according to a HLHL Prize winners list
which appeared in today's Beijing-based "People's Daily."
</P>
<P>
Each of the 63 winners of the HLHL Science and Technology Promotion
Prize will receive 150,000 HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
The HLHL Foundation was established in 1994 by the S.H. Ho
Foundation, Kan-Kui Leung, Ho Tim and Wei Lun Foundation in Hong
Kong with 100 million HK dollar donations from each.
</P>
<P>
The foundation has awarded 121 Chinese scientists since 1994.
</P>
<P>
