<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Benefits from Solar Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Most residents of northwest
China's Tibet Autonomous Region, even the lamas, who used to
regard solar energy as an insult to the Sun God, have been
benefiting from various solar-powered facilities.
</P>
<P>
With an average sunshine time totalling from 3,100 to 3,400
hours each year, Tibet ranks second in the world in terms of
receiving the amount of solar radiation.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has invested over 17 million yuan
(about 2.2 million US dollars) to build two million-plus square
meters of greenhouse area, 80,000-square meters of housing with a
solar energy heating system, and about 100,000 solar-powered
kitchen ranges, according to Zhang Jie, director of the Tibetan
Solar Energy Research and Demonstration Center.
</P>
<P>
She added that scientists and researchers have been working
since the early 1980s to promote the solar energy-related
technology in the region so as to conserve resources and protect
the environment.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is going to build the country's largest solar energy
power station in Ando with the highest power-generating capacity
and most advanced equipment in the country in a move to maintain
the region's leading role in the field.
</P>
<P>
The Shuanghu Solar Energy Power Station, currently China's
largest solar energy power station, was set up in Tibet in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The region has applied 1,000 kilowatts of solar battery power
to the radio, TV broadcasting, telecommunications and other
transmitting systems in the area, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
"Various facilities using solar energy in Tibet have saved
conventional energy sources amounting to more than 110,000 tons of
standard coal each year," said Zhang Jie. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
