<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks Going on to Avert Teachers Strike in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Serious consultations are
taking place in a bid to find solutions to avert the planned
national teachers strike, the East African Standard today quoted
Kenyan Education Minister Joseph Kamotho as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister emphasized here Monday that "we hope for a
workable solution before the expiry of the deadline (October 1)"
of the strike call by the Kenya National Union of Teachers (KNUT)
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry had hoped the stalemate would be resolved
between KNUT and the Ministry of Labor, adding, "the matter is
now under very active discussion at government level."
</P>
<P>
Since KNUT issued a notice of the strike to be called on
October 1, many branches of the teachers union all over the
country have supported the move.
</P>
<P>
Taita Taveta District teachers vowed to proceed with the
strike unless the Ministry of Education adhered to their specific
demands.
</P>
<P>
teachers in Kwale also resolved to support the October 1
strike and told Kamotho to resign.
</P>
<P>
KNUT Busia branch called on all local teachers to "participate
fully" in the planned October 1 strike.
</P>
<P>
Keiyo District was warned "not to dare" report to their
respective schools on October 1.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with top KNUT officials here last night,
Kenyan Labor Minister Philip Masinde criticized KNUT officials
for resorting to the strike option.
</P>
<P>
The union is demanding a salary increase ranging between 150
and 200 percent and has also called for the resignation of
Education Minister Kamotho.
</P>
<P>
But, the Kenyan government agreed to give an increase ranging
between 10 and 28 percent, which Kenyan teachers rejected as "an
insult to their intellect".
</P>
<P>
Kamotho pointed out that "surely it is not realistic for
anybody to ask for a 200 percent hike. The teachers must be told
the truth about the pressures from the International Monetary
Fund and general poverty."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Kenyan Ministry of Labor had formed a
committee to address the issues raised by the teachers union.
</P>
</TEXT>
