<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The death toll from Saturday's raids in western
Kenyas' Lokiriama and Lorengipi areas, about six kilometers from
the border with Uganda, has risen to 46, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Kenyan police confirmed that 31 people including
nine raiders were killed in the cattle rustling. The raiders,
believed to be Pokot and Tepes from Uganda, took away hundreds of
domestic animals. (Kenya-Ugandan Rustlers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Twenty-one people in a village in Tabora
Region, southwestern Tanzania, have been admitted to hospital
after eating some food suspected to have been poisoned with DDT,
the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred on Monday morning after the victims'
families had bought maize flour in a shop, the report quoted
Regional Police Commander Ignas Mtana as confirming
it. (Tanzania-Poison Food)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR), said here today that the
annual meetings of the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF), which opened here today, is of special meaning for
Hong Kong shortly after its reunification with China.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the meetings, Tung said the
presence of Premier Li Peng and many distinguished guests of the
international financial community signified their strong support
for Hong Kong and underlined its status as a leading international
financial center.
</P>
<P>
The meetings, scheduled for September 23 and 25 in Hong Kong,
also provide a unique opportunity for people from all over the
world to witness at first hand the pride and confidence and the
continuing prosperity and stability of Hong Kong under the
framework of "one country, two systems", said
Tung. (HK-WB/IMF/Tung)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- A bus driver asleep at the wheel led to a fatal
accident which killed 33 and injured 16 in Vietnam last Friday
morning, press reports said here today.
</P>
<P>
The bus went off the road and tumbled into a lagoon in
Vietnam's central coastal province of Phu Yen. (Vietnam-Bus
Tragedy) 
