<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Zhu Awards 65 Scientists in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji
here today gave the Ho Leung Ho Lee Foundation awards to 65 noted
Chinese scholars from the interior areas.
</P>
<P>
The Ho Leung Ho Lee Foundation was established in Hong Kong in
1994 with total funds amounting to 400 million HK dollars (51.28
million U.S. dollars), donated by the S. H. Ho Foundation Ltd.,
the late Dr. Kau-Kui Leung, Dr. Ho Tim, and Dr. Lee Quo-wei's Wei
Lun Foundation Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), was present at the Fourth Award
Presentation Ceremony of the Ho Leung Ho Lee Foundation held at
Hang Seng Bank Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Zhu extended his congratulations to the winners and paid
regards to the founders of the foundation and their families.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said it is of great significance for the foundation, set up
by the Chinese, to award prizes to noted scientists of China's
interior area after Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to catch up with the world's advanced
levels in science and technology. To this end, he said, greater
importance must be attached to education and science and
technology when China strives for modernization.
</P>
<P>
Professors Qian Weichang and Wang Zhongcheng were awarded the
prize of science and technology achievements for their
contributions in the fields of mechanics and medical science
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-three other scientists received awards for progress in
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
So far, a total of 13 scientists have won the achievement
awards and 173 the progress award.
</P>
<P>
The primary purpose of the foundation is to award annual prizes
to distinguished Chinese scholars on the mainland for their
achievements in science, technology, medicine and other
disciplines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
