<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Borrows $27.5M to Meet Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government
borrowed 15.1 billion Shillings (about 27.5 million U.S. Dollars)
in the 1996/97 fiscal year to finance the budget deficit, the
Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Of the amount, 12.8 billion Shillings (23.3 million Dollars)
were from non-bank private sectors, the report quoted the
Quarterly Budget Review from the Ministry of Finance as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 7.7-billion-Shilling (14 million Dollars) debt, owed by
the government to the Central Bank of Kenya, was repaid.
</P>
<P>
All governmental borrowing during the year was in the form of
funded debt, with the Treasury bill being the leading debt
instrument.
</P>
<P>
The stock of public debt has been declining over the last four
years, to stand at 449 billion Shillings (8.2 billion Dollars) by
the end of June 1997, compared to 489 billion Shillings (nine
billion Dollars) in June 1993.
</P>
<P>
The decline was due to a continuous drop in the level of
external debt which has gone down by 16 percent over the period.
</P>
<P>
Total government revenue fell short of target from 6.2 billion
Shillings (11.3 million Dollars) during the 1996/97 fiscal year
and 149.2 billion Shillings (2.7 billion Dollars), or 26.4
percent of the gross domestic product were collected as revenue
that year.
</P>
<P>
Total expenditure and net lending increased by 8.6 billion
Shillings (15.6 million Dollars) during the year over the 1995/96
year to 160.8 billion Shillings (three billion Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
