<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Cooperation to Be Sought to Minimize Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will seek
cooperation from the other ASEAN members to look into ways to
minimize the impact of severe currency fluctuations on their
economies, especially on trade and investment, a Malaysian
official said today.
</P>
<P>
International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz told a
news conference here that Malaysia would bring up the currency
crisis affecting several ASEAN countries at the 29th ASEAN
Economic Ministers' Meeting to be held here from October 16 to 18.
</P>
<P>
The minister said one way the ASEAN countries could minimize
the impact was to develop specific industries in specific
countries within ASEAN, which were most cost-effective.
</P>
<P>
She said that whatever strategy the economic ministers might
adopt would probably be brought forward to the ASEAN Leaders'
Informal Summit to be held here in December.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, Laos,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two months, ASEAN currencies have been battered
by foreign speculations, causing them to decline significantly
with Malaysia's Ringgit having fallen by 20 percent against the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah dismissed the speculation that the currency crisis
would impede the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) process, saying "all
of us are in the same boat."
</P>
<P>
She called on Malaysian manufacturers to use the opportunity
created by the depreciation of the local currency to increase
exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
