<HEADLINE> Ancient Nanjing City Goes Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Nanjing, capital of east
China's Jiangsu Province, has 367 hectares more green area than
two years ago when it had 9,253 hectares of tree-covered space in
its urban areas, according to the Nanjing Bureau of Parks and
Woods.
</P>
<P>
The city has increased its green area coverage to 40 percent,
or about eight square meters per person, continuing to rank among
the top green capital cities in China, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing has taken great efforts to build ten green squares with
a total area of 260,000 square meters and plant nearly 100,000
trees along 50 streets in last two years. It has also newly built
13 parks covering 40,000 square meters and flower beds totaling
22,700 square meters, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In its suburbs, Nanjing has built hundreds of hectares of
shelter-forests to prevent industrial pollution and beautify the
surroundings, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing now has an urban environment further improved by the
green project, and has recently been honored as "State City of
Gardens" by the Ministry of Construction. Consequently, Nanjing
has hosted more and more international conventions, national
conferences and trade expositions.
</P>
<P>
On top of that, Nanjing has witnessed a boom in tourism, the
official noted. In the first half of this year the numbers of
tourists from home and abroad have increased by 15 percent and 30
percent respectively from the same period of last year, with the
total tourism income of 4.8 billion yuan (about 580 million US
dollars), up by 20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
