<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Chief Calls for Efforts to Meet Challenge of Inclusion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James
Wolfensohn today called for "a quantum leap" in the development
effort to narrow the gap between the rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the Annual Meetings of the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Wolfensohn
outlined a plan to meet what he called "the challenge of
inclusion", which is "the key development challenge of our time".
</P>
<P>
"Our goal must be to reduce these disparities across and within
countries, to bring more and more people into the economic
mainstream, to promote equitable access to the benefits of
development regardless of nationality, race or gender," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must recognize that we are living with a time bomb and
unless we take action now, it could explode in our children's
faces," he warned.
</P>
<P>
If world leaders do not act now, he warned, the number of
people living in acute poverty could grow from 3 billion to 5
billion in the next 30 years. The environment would deteriorate
over that time, and the number of wars could increase.
</P>
<P>
Whether seen as a social, economic and moral issue, "this is a
challenge we cannot afford to ignore", the president said. He
called on all developing countries to "educate their people,
ensure their health, give them voice and justice, financial
systems that work, and sound economic policies".
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn highlighted the achievements of East Asian countries
in lifting people from poverty and sharing the benefits of
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent turbulence in the region's financial
market, he said, "We still expect long-term growth and poverty
reduction to be strong."
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the Bank is scaling up its work to
restructure banking and financial systems in developing countries,
and pointed to East Asia's recent currency turbulence as evidence
of the need for such assistance.
</P>
<P>
The "challenge of inclusion" is too big to be handled by any
government or development agency alone, he said, emphasizing
"partnership" resting on four pillars as a "cornerstone" of the
concerted efforts.
</P>
<P>
First and foremost, the government and the people of developing
countries must be in the driver's seat, exercising choice and
setting their own objectives for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, partnerships must be inclusive, with involvement of
bilateral and multilateral agencies, labor organizations,
non-government organizations, foundations and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, development agencies should help all countries, but
concentrate on those which were most likely to use external
support effectively. "We must be selective in how we use our
resources," he said.
</P>
<P>
And finally, the development community must aim for a quantum
leap in results by focusing heavily on social and human
development, rural and environmental development, and financial
and private sector development.
</P>
<P>
As the ninth president of the prestigious international
financial institution, Wolfensohn also outlined a number of
changes now underway within the World Bank Group, designed to make
it more effective in its mission of reducing poverty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
