<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Launch National Women's Employment Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Government is
likely to launch a National Action Plan (ANP) in the last week of
October for ensuring the employment of women at all levels, it was
learned here today from an official source.
</P>
<P>
The ANP, has been already approved by Bangladesh Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina, the sources said, adding that it was prepared on
the basis of assessment of 12 ministries.
</P>
<P>
The source noted that the plan emphasizes the strategy of
mainstreaming women's development into government policies and
programs.
</P>
<P>
The plan has been formulated to remove all the disparities
against women at all levels in the country, a high-ranking
official from the Ministry of Women and Children Affairs said.
</P>
<P>
It has proposed in the NAP to explore the possibilities whether
women can be appointed to the post of Bangladesh's permanent
representative to the United Nations or to the post of Chairperson
of the University Grant Commission, and to enhance the appointment
of women to the posts of ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
According to the existing quota for each of the ministries,
female should be given appointment at least 10 percent of Class 1
gazetted officers' posts and 15 percent in the case of
non-gazetted posts.
</P>
<P>
"But no ministry is complying with it," the official pointed
out, adding that as a result, there were less than five percent
representation of women in Class 1 gazetted officers' posts and
less that 10 percent in the case of non-gazettes posts.
</P>
<P>
The NAP will ensure accountability in all the ministries in
implementing the policies regarding women's and children's
development, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
