<HEADLINE> WB/IMF Meetings Have Special Meaning for HK: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR),
said here today that the annual meetings of the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), which opened here today, is of
special meaning for Hong Kong shortly after its reunification with
China.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the meetings, Tung said the
presence of Premier Li Peng and many distinguished guests of the
international financial community signified their strong support
for Hong Kong and underlined its status as a leading international
financial center.
</P>
<P>
The meetings, scheduled for September 23 and 25 in Hong Kong,
also provide a unique opportunity for people from all over the
world to witness at first hand the pride and confidence and the
continuing prosperity and stability of Hong Kong under the
framework of "one country, two systems", said the Chief Executive.
</P>
<P>
Tung continued: "July 1 has come and gone. We, who live and
work in Hong Kong, continue to work hard for an even more
successful and prosperous future."
</P>
<P>
He told the participants that business is as usual in Hong Kong
after July 1: the SAR government has been functioning normally,
economy continues to grow, there has been no change in life style,
 and recent surveys have shown that 78 percent of the Hong Kong
people expressed confidence over Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamental reason for our confidence is the solid promise
of the Basis Law," said Tung. "All the factors critical to Hong
Kong's success have been enshrined in the Basic Law, which
provides a constitutional framework for the HKSAR."
</P>
<P>
He accredited Hong Kong's remarkable success over the past
decades to free competitive environment, rule of law, a level
playing field, clean and efficient civil service.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive noted that the fixed exchange rate regime
is the anchor of Hong Kong's monetary and financial stability. He
said: "We do not intend to compete internationally on the basis of
exchange rate adjustment. We compete equally and fairly in terms
of private sector productivity and public sector efficiency. Our
open markets, free trade and sound finance are the hallmarks of
Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Asia may be going through a period of consolidation, he said,
adding that many countries that have suffered from the recent
turmoil in the financial market will soon be on a rebound.
</P>
<P>
"The continuing rapid growth and development in many parts of
Asia will bring new opportunities to Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
