<HEADLINE> Nagano Olympics Organizers Agree to Consider Raising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Nagano Winter Olympic officials
are considering new environmentally friendly ways of raising the
starting point of the men's downhill race, which the International
Ski Federation says falls short of Olympic standards.
</P>
<P>
Suggestions presented by federation will be passed on for
government consideration, Makoto Kobayashi, director general of
the Nagano Olympic Committee, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
International Ski Federation secretary general Gian-Franco
Kasper assured Japan that the proposed course would not damage
surrounding national park land.
</P>
<P>
Kasper said: "We can guarantee the Japanese people there will
be absolutely no construction that will touch the ground."
</P>
<P>
The men's downhill will be one of the main events of the
February 7-22 games. But the course has been panned as too easy
for a top international competition.
</P>
<P>
The ski federation and the International Olympic Committee want
the start raised to 1,800 meters from the current 1,680 meters.
</P>
<P>
Nagano officials have countered that a longer course would
require building platforms for cameras, putting up safety nets to
protect athletes or using chemicals to harden the surface -- all
of which is illegal in national parks.
</P>
<P>
Under the latest proposal the starting area would be
constructed of snow. FIS has said chemicals need not be used
within the national park boundaries, and that compromises could be
worked out on the other issues as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
