<HEADLINE> Gray to Become ICC President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Australian Cricket Board
(ACB) director Malcolm Gray will replace India's Jagmohan Dalmiya
as president of the International Cricket Council (ICC) for a
three-year stint from the year 2000, According to reports from
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Gray lost the previous election to Dalmiya, who triumphed with
the support of minor associated members of the ICC plus India,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
ACB chairman Denis Rogers said that Gray, 57, would become the
next president because Australia had the right to nominate
Dalmiya's successor.
</P>
<P>
"The changes we are seeing in sport bring increased pressure on
players, management and policy makers and we have to ensure that
cricket is relevant and positioned strongly into the future," Gray
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Gray joined the ACB in 1983 as one of Victoria's three
directors to the board and was ACB chairman from 1986-89. 
</P>
</TEXT>
