<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sailing Start From City Downtown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 23 (Xinhua) -- With their whistles blowing,
three luxury yachts slowly sailed out of a harbor in the Funan
River in this capital city of Sichuan province recently, cheered
on by tens of thousands of local residents watching from the
riverbanks.
</P>
<P>
The southwest China city recently resumed its shipping business
after half a century's suspension caused by serious water
pollution.
</P>
<P>
"It is rare in China that passenger vessels can sail in the
downtown area of a big city," said Chengdu Mayor Wang Rongxuan,
adding that some ancient poets even recorded such grand scenes in
their verses.
</P>
<P>
Prior to 1993, when clean-up work began on the river, some
100,000 local residents had turned out to get away from the dirt
and foul odor.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the city government has invested a total of 2.7
billion yuan (325 million US dollars) to clear the river, build
new banks, plant trees and flowers, open parks nearby, and remove
600-plus wastewater dumping pipes.
</P>
<P>
"The smelly river, at last, was transformed into a green
necklace for the city," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The ecological project received more than 20 million yuan (2.4
million US dollars) of donations from local residents, and it also
drew attention from cities in Britain and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The city government has also worked out plans for the next five
to ten years to recover the water transport between Chengdu and
the Yangtze River region.
</P>
<P>
"Boats may sail directly to cities of Nanjing, Yangzhou and
Shanghai on the lower reaches of the country's longest river in
the near future," said the mayor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
