<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Children's Health Approaches World Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The general health reports
on children in Shanghai, have approached the standards set by the
World Health Organization (WHO) in terms of both weight and height.
</P>
<P>
A survey from the Department of Children's Health shows that
the growth of children under age seven has improved, compared with
ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
The average weight of urban and rural children in this age
group increased by 0.54 kg and 0.5 kg respectively, while their
height increased by 1.17 cm and 1.38 cm.
</P>
<P>
The growth indices of children under age one and between the
ages of four and six have met the WHO's standards.
</P>
<P>
Health experts attributed the improvement in children's health
to the effective health care measures provided by communities.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1980s, many clinics specializing in prenatal
health care, particularly treatment of liver and heart diseases in
 newborns, have been established in the city.
</P>
<P>
The health care networks for women and children at all levels
have set up a "Children's Health Card" system to monitor and
record the growth of children under seven and spread information
about children's health care to new mothers.
</P>
<P>
The health organizations also improved the prevention work of
common diseases among children, such as children's anemia, rickets
and digestive and respiratory ailments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
