<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 33 People Killed in Vietnamese Bus Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A bus driver asleep at the
wheel led to a fatal accident which killed 33 and injured 16 in
Vietnam last Friday morning, press reports said here today.
</P>
<P>
The bus went off the road and tumbled into a lagoon in
Vietnam's central coastal province of Phu Yen.
</P>
<P>
Survivors said the sleepy driver, wakened by the terrified
cries of the passengers, tried but failed to gain control of the
bus, which was sliding all over the wet road.
</P>
<P>
The driver, who survived the crash, fled the scene of the
accident.
</P>
<P>
A witness said the bus tumbled over and over, then hit a rock
outcropping beneath the road before it sank into the salt water.
</P>
<P>
"Some people and luggage were flung out of the bus", said a
local fisherman who rescued four passengers from the ill-fated bus.
</P>
<P>
Police and local people rushed to the crash site, but could
rescue only 22 people from the bus which was submerged in seven
meters of water.
</P>
<P>
All the bodies of victims have been found and identified.
</P>
<P>
Despite the great efforts of the traffic police, traffic
injuries and fatalities have continued to rise in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Drivers' carelessness was the primary cause of the
wrecks. Poorly maintained infrastructure system is also to blame
for many accidents.
</P>
<P>
Mismanagement of the traffic system and loose enforcement of
the laws has turned the country's roads into a motorized
free-for-all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
