<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khirbash Outlines Priorities for World Bank, IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Mohammed Khirbash, chairman
of the Boards of Governors of the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), today outlined three major priorities for the
two international institutions as the financial cooperation,
governance and help for poor countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the 1997 Annual Meetings of
the World Bank and IMF at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition
Center, Khirbash underlined the need for all member-countries to
accelerate efforts to achieve sustained growth and harmonious
development.
</P>
<P>
"Let me highlight three areas where a strengthened common
effort is making a significant difference: financial sector
cooperation, governance and the initiative for heavily-indebted
poor countries," said Khirbash, also minister of state for finance
and industry of the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
On financial sector cooperation, he said "enhanced cooperation
would ensure that financial sector problems are promptly
identified, and that each institution takes the lead in its areas
of primary concern."
</P>
<P>
As to the governance issue, he said, "Promoting transparency,
accountability, and institutional capacity are critical to
successful, sound and equitable development."
</P>
<P>
Touching upon the Debt Initiative for heavily Indebted Poor
Countries (HIPC), he said that the initiative "is a striking
development and a radical departure addressing the debt problems
of these countries in a comprehensive fashion, including debt owed
to multilateral institutions. We look forward to continued
expeditious implementation of this initiative and further transfer
of concessional resources to developing countries."
</P>
<P>
The world economic environment remains "broadly favorable for
the achievement of our objectives," Khirbash noted, and most
countries are achieving growth, with increased attention to an
investment in people and with an increased concern for the
environment.
</P>
<P>
However, there still exist some dangers in economic growth, he
said, noting as an example the recent financial crisis in the
Southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
He urged the World Bank and the IMF to make further efforts in
minimizing the dangers and in fostering liberalization of capital
movements in ways that are consistent with a sound international
financial system.
</P>
<P>
Khirbash also called on all member-countries of the two
international institutions to go forward for an increasingly
integrated world economy.
</P>
<P>
Declaring the annual meetings open, he expressed thanks to the
Chinese Government and the people of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) for their "generous hospitality in
this beautiful city in this historic year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
