<HEADLINE> Capital Cinemas Report Record Box-office Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- After a protracted slump in
ticket sales, cinemas in the Chinese capital are reaping record
box-office revenue.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since last year, 76 cinemas in Beijing
reported a total revenue income of about 100 million yuan (12
million US dollars) and market analysts have projected their 1997
turnover to be in excess of 110 million yuan (13.25 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The soaring business profit was resultant from the
establishment of a shareholding movie business entity early last
year that put an end to the monopoly of the municipal film
company.
</P>
<P>
Under the unified movie release system, the 76 cinemas formerly
generated a yearly income of 30 million yuan (3.6 million US
dollars to 40 million yuan (4.8 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new movie company has continued to tap the market by
launching unprecedented ad campaigns. A domestic-made movie "The
Days Without A Hero," for example, fetched a total box-office
revenue of 5.8 million yuan. One out of four Beijing residents is
said to have seen the movie.
</P>
<P>
And the growing number of cinema-goers reflects the quality of
the movies generally are on the rise, industry analysts pointed
out, especially as the drab propaganda content is waning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
