<HEADLINE> Iranian Team to Visit Pakistan Next Month: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 23 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian delegation is
expected to arrive here in the first week of October to know
findings of the ongoing probe into the murder of five Iranians
last week in Pakistan, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will be headed by a cabinet minister and
"because of strict security, the dates of the visit are not being
made public," the News quoted an official of the Foreign Office as
saying.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the Iranian minister will have meetings at
the ministries of foreign affairs, interior and defense, and be
briefed about the investigation, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday five Iranian National Civil Aviation trainees,
who came here in August for two months of training, were killed by
three unidentified gunmen at Rawalpindi, the sister city of the
Pakistani capital.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the shooting, Iran lodged a strong protest
against Pakistan over the killing and demanded swift arrest and
punishment of the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
Expressing their profound grief over the killing, Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, President Farooq Leghari and Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan assured that the government would give
exemplary punishment to the culprits.
</P>
<P>
The News reported on Monday that the teams of army and police
investigating into the killing had made no headway so far.
</P>
