<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vast Oilfield Discovered in South Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Italian state-owned oil firm
Agip has discovered a vast oilfield in the Agri valley in south
Italy, the ANSA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Agri oilfield, which is believed to be the largest in the
European continent, has a proven deposit of 622 million
barrels. So far, it has four wells that produce oil.
</P>
<P>
Agip plans to invest 2.457 trillion lire (approximately 1.4
billion U.S. dollars) in the oilfield in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Italy, long plagued with an oil shortage, started oil
exploration in the Agri valley as early as 1936 but had to give up
after failing to find oil at the depth of 300 meters.
</P>
<P>
Oil was struck in the valley in 1980 after drilling 3,000
meters deep, but it has no commercial value.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, oil gushed out of some wells when they had
drilled deep under 5,000 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
