<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Traders Urged to Prevent Jasmine Rice Adulteration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Foreign Trade
Department has called on Thai rice millers and exporters to pack
their jasmine rice in five-kg bags, in stead of large sacks, to
prevent adulteration, according to the Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
Jasmine rice, now in high demand in the world market, is
currently packed in 100-kg sacks. The rice is often repackaged
into small bags for retailing. Adulteration is often done at this
repackaging stage.
</P>
<P>
The call has been made after a number of complaints have been
filed by foreign importers alleging that Thai fragrant rice
shipped overseas has been mixed with non-jasmine rice.
</P>
<P>
The department has also called on millers and exporters to
label their bags with their own trade marks.
</P>
<P>
Jasmine rice adulteration has also caused concern to Thai
Commerce Minister Narongchai Akrasanee. He said if the problem is
not urgently resolved, foreign confidence in fragrant rice will
erode, just at a time when it is becoming increasingly popular
with overseas consumers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
