<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Crack Down on Out-of-Date Food, Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government is
enhancing its cracking down on expired food and medicines on sale
in the markets.
</P>
<P>
Today's official paper The New Light of Myanmar quoted a
reminder issued by the Ministry of Health as notifying that all
brands of bottled water, traditional and imported Western
medicines, tinned provisions, foodstuff and preserves packed in
plastic cases or bags on sale should bear the date of manufacture
and expiry.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Myanmar health authorities banned some 14
brands of traditional drugs and 26 local and foreign brands of
purified bottled water for public consumption in the country for
their failure to meet the required standard after examination.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar enacted the National Food Law in March this year,
forming a special Food and Drug Authority in its bid to enable the
public to consume food of genuine quality, free from danger and
hygienic problems, and to control and regulate the production,
import, export, storage, distribution and sale of food
systematically.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Explains Principles for Helping Developing Countries (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li Peng said, "Fourthly, countries should learn from each other
and complement each other with respective advantages."
</P>
<P>
Both the developed and the developing countries have their own
strengths and advantages. The developed countries are advanced in
science and technology and strong in financial capital, while the
developing countries are rich in natural and human resources and
large in market potential.
</P>
<P>
The economic interdependence between the two groups is
deepening steadily, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Faced with such increasingly serious global issues as
environment, poverty, debt and refugees, the two sides will find
it hard to cope with the challenges unless they can learn from and
complement each other and work together to bring about common
prosperity, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Fifthly, it is essential to choose a development road
suited to one's own national conditions."
</P>
<P>
Developing countries do need a favorable external environment
in order to eliminate poverty and achieve economic take-off, Li
noted, Yet in the final analysis, they must depend on their own
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Proceeding from their actual situation at home and in light of
their needs and possibilities, the developing countries should
work out effective domestic policies and actively conduct economic
restructuring in response to shifting economic and technological
trends in the world.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, South-South cooperation in every field should
be strengthened and North-South relations improved and further
promoted.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng said, "Sixthly, international cooperation in financial
field should be reinforced."
</P>
<P>
Free flow of capital across national boundaries is a strong
feature of the development of world economy. It can facilitate
absorption of capital by various countries but may also carry
financial risks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Being prone to have such risks, developing countries may also
become easy targets of international financial speculation.
Financial crises will do no country any good. The international
community, international financial institutions included, should
play a positive role in maintaining international financial
stability, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Li
said, have played a useful role in promoting the world economic
growth, economic exchanges among counties and economic and social
progress of the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
With rapid advancement of science and technology and
unprecedented expansion of economic cooperation, the world is
moving towards multipolarity with accelerated pace, he added.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank Group and the IMF, as the most influential
multilateral financial institutions, will preserve their vigor and
hold out a bright future only when they can undergo timely
readjustments and reform in keeping with the new and shifting
world situation and give expression to the reasonable demands of
the developing countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Army to Withdraw From Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Command of
the U.S. army will begin to leave Panama next Thursday, after more
than 30 years' presence in this country, a Panamanian Foreign
Ministry spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Southern Command, the U.S. army for operations in
Central and South America, will move to Miami, the United States,
the spokesman told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
About 770 civil and military officers will leave Panama.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal is of historic significance for Latin America,
because the U.S. military presence symbolizes U.S. hegemony over
the region during this century.
</P>
<P>
"The dismantling of the Southern Command headquarters
represents a step forward to the definitive withdrawal of
U.S. military bases and the return of the Canal to Panamanian
hands," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Torrijos-Carter treaty signed by Panama and the
United States in 1977, the United States must transfer the Panama
Canal to Panama and the U.S. military forces will pull out from
the country before December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The first American military force was installed in Panama in
1914 to protect the canal facilities.
</P>
<P>
In 1963, for a wider operating control in the zone and more
influence in Latin America's political and military affairs, the
U.S. government established the Southern Command.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, the number of U.S. soldiers has
reduced from 18,500 in 1994 to 5,600 this year in accordance with
the Torrijos-Carter treaty.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that by October 1, only 4,400 U.S. soldiers and
officers will stay in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0223 </DOCNO>
