<HEADLINE> China, EU Expect Broader Economic-Trade Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China and the European Union
(EU) have strengthened their economic and trade relations in the
past years and there are prospects for greater cooperation in such
areas, senior officials from the two sides said here today.
</P>
<P>
Relations between China and the EU have been growing
satisfactorily in general since the latter's implementation of a
long-term China policy in July 1995, with efforts made by both
sides, said Qian Qichen, vice-premier and foreign minister of
China in meeting with EU leaders.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who is attending the 52nd session of the United Nations
General Assembly, met with Jacques F. Poos, deputy prime minister
and minister of foreign affairs of Luxembourg, the current EU
presidency, Hans Van Mierlo, vice prime minister and foreign
minister of the Netherlands, the last EU Presidency, and Bobin
Cook, foreign secretary of Britain, the next EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
In their meeting, Qian said China and the EU have increased
exchanges of high-level visit and contacts and political
consultations in recent years that pushed the development of
economic and trade relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Qian also, on request, briefed his EU counterparts on the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China, which ended
last week.
</P>
<P>
He said the congress showed to the world that China will
adhere to the course of deepening reforms and opening up to the
outside world which was drawn by the late Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
China will meet the goal drawn at the congress, which will
provide greater opportunities for China and EU nations as well as
other states to expand their economic cooperation and trade
relations.
</P>
<P>
In their turn, Poos and the other EU officials said that the EU
appreciated China's rapid development and attached importance to
its ties with China.
</P>
<P>
They said the EU saw new scopes for further strengthening its
economic and trade ties with China after China's party congress,
which laid out the plan for deepening reform and opening-up to the
outside world and the nation's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The EU was willing to broaden its cooperation with China and
increase mutual understandings so as to promote bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the issue of China's accession to
the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier noted that great progress has been
achieved in the talks between China and some other nations. The EU
should also take an more active and realistic attitude toward the
matter and push the process moving.
</P>
<P>
He urged the EU to take measures to end its protectionism and
promote the development of trade with other nations.
</P>
<P>
EU leaders agreed to make active efforts for China's early
accession to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
On the human right issue, Qian reiterated China's position for
dialogue on the bases of equality and mutual respect in settling
human right issues between nations.
</P>
<P>
Poos agreed for new ways of cooperation and exchanges in moving
its differences with China on the human right issue.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed United Nations reforms and other
international issues of common concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
