<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Police Seize Tamil Rebels' Arms Lorry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's police on Monday
seized a lorry used by the Tamil rebels to transport explosives,
firearms, ammunition and suicide kits from the North to Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested three Tamil rebels who were fleeing in the
lorry, in Vavuniya town in the Northern province, the local press
said today.
</P>
<P>
The lorry owner who had a contract for regular haulage of goods
to and from Vavuniya had fled from Colombo earlier when the police
in the capital city went hunting for him.
</P>
<P>
The lorry was wanted in connection with an abortive attempt by
the rebels to attack the Ratmalana Airport in the suburb of
Colombo which is now used as an airforce base.
</P>
<P>
A large arms cache of the rebels was discovered on September 16
in a safe house at Ratmalana, some 20 kilometers south of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The plot was revealed when two terrorists of the suicide squad
were arrested for spying in the airport premises. Subsequently
five others were arrested but their leader and four others managed
to escape.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the large cache of arms, including explosives,
hand grenades and suicide kits, police found maps of government
buildings in Colombo which the rebels had apparently planned to
target.  
</P>
</TEXT>
