<HEADLINE> Bangkok to Seek Loan to Increase Jasmine Rice Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is to borrow about
330 million U.S. dollars from the World Bank to boost the
production of jasmine fragrant rice in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture and Cooperatives Ministry is drafting a
proposal to the World Bank, which is expected to give a soft loan
for the purpose, according to the Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
In recent years there is a strong demand in the world market
for jasmine fragrant rice, of which Thailand is the only producer.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to improve irrigation networks in two
northeastern provinces, Nakhon Ratchasima and Buri Ram, and to
improve rice seeds.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is trying to find ways to solve soil salinity in
the target areas to double the yield of fragrant rice from about
450 kilograms per rai (one hectare equals to 6.25 rai) to 1,000
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that improved irrigation networks will help dilute
salinity in the soil.  
</P>
</TEXT>
