<HEADLINE> China's Energy Sector Greets Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China needs and welcomes
foreign capital and technology to help accelerate its huge but
still inadequate energy supply, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
China, the world's third largest bank of energy resources, after
the United States and Russia, had used some 12.1 billion US
dollars in foreign investment to build facilities for its power
industry by 1994.
</P>
<P>
The capital helped build 64 large and medium-sized power
projects with a total installed capacity of 40.7 GW, of which 19.6
GW is now in operation.
</P>
<P>
The coal industry had absorbed 3.76 billion US dollars in
foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
In early 1993, the Chinese Government announced that foreign
investors could participate in the power industry by setting up
co-operatives or joint ventures or establishing solely
foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Power companies from Japan, Kuwait, France, Britain, Italy and
Canada, supported financially by their respective governments, are
vying for a share in China's power market.
</P>
<P>
US companies have participated in China's coal, petroleum and
natural gas sectors, and have been well repaid. The prospects of
co-operation between the two countries in other energy sectors
such as coal and petroleum are also bright.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government has made unremitting efforts to improve
the domestic investment environment.
</P>
<P>
The Law on Electric Power, which protects power investors and
ensures balanced generation, supply and use of electricity, went
into effect in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
And the provinces and autonomous regions are empowered to
examine and approve joint mining projects with a contracted value
of less than 3.6 million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
