<HEADLINE> Small Town Chosen for National Agricultural Hi-Tech Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Yangling, a small town in
northwest China, was chosen last March by the State to be the site
for construction of a national agricultural high-tech industry
demonstration zone.
</P>
<P>
Yangling, 90 km west of Xi'an, capital of northwest China's
Shaanxi province, is considered ideal in the pioneering
role as the town, though with an area no bigger than four square
kilometers, has two colleges, five research institutes and three
polytechnic schools devoted to agriculture, forestry and hydraulic
engineering, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Science gardens, industrial sub-zones and experimental
bases will built at the national agricultural high-tech industry
demonstration zone.
</P>
<P>
The science garden consists of all the schools, research institutes
and their experimental fields in the town, while the industrial
sub-zone will be composed of 13 agricultural high-tech industries
which are designed to set a good example of industrialization of
agriculture for the rest of the country and will be open to all
investors.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, Yangling has trained more than 60,000
professional personnel in the agricultural field. More than 5,000
agricultural research projects conducted at the facility have come
to fruition. About 70 percent of the laboratory research has been
turned into marketable products.
</P>
<P>
The direct economic returns resulting from the application of
laboratory research of Yangling have exceeded 20 billion yuan,
said the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Central Bank Cuts Interest Rates Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia, the central
bank, for the fourth time since September 4 lowered Monday its
benchmark interest rates for one to three month papers by one to
two percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The one-month Bank Indonesia certificate (SBI) rate was reduced
from 23 percent to 21 percent, the three-month rate from 21
percent to 19 percent, one week rate from 18 percent to 17 percent
and two week rate from 20 percent to 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
SBI's overnight interest rate was maintained at 15 percent, and
those of six months at 12.125 percent and 12 months at 12.75
percent.
</P>
<P>
"The reduction is part of our commitment to continue lowering
interest rates. We just wait for the right time to do it," the
bank's foreign exchange division vice chairman Bambang Sindu said
here last night.
</P>
<P>
The central bank raised its benchmark interest rates to as high
as 30 percent on August 19 to curb massive speculative attacks on
the rupiah after its free floating on August 14.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah was trading at 3,020/3,030 against the U.S. dollar
late Monday afternoon from its opening of 2,970, or down by 45
points compared with last Friday's close at 2,975/2,985 per U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Sindu discounted suggestions that the rate cuts prompted the
rupiah to weaken, saying, 'I don't think the rupiah was weaker
because of the rate cuts."
</P>
<P>
"It's more likely because of the Malaysian ringgit weakness,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, share prices on the Jakarta stock exchange gained
0.2 percent following the SBI's rate cut, with the composite index
closed up 4.522 points at 535.601.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the upward momentum, amid regional stock falls,
was sustained by the interest rate cut, which would make
investment in equity more attractive.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen more than 10 percent in the past month
and nearly 25 percent since January this year following offshore
speculative attacks on the currency and a rush by local companies
to hedge their foreign borrowings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
