<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forbidden City Wall Renovation Project to Be Finished Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The renovation of the wall
surrounding the Forbidden City or the Palace Museum, is expected
to be completed before National Day, which falls on October 1.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1420 A.D. and covering 720,000 square meters, the
Forbidden City was the imperial palace of two feudal dynasties and
is China's largest and most well-preserved cluster of ancient
building structures.
</P>
<P>
The wall stretches more than 3,000 meters around the Palace
Museum and is ten meters high.
</P>
<P>
Pei Huanlu, deputy curator of the Palace Museum, explained
that deteriorating bricks from the wall are being replaced by new
ones of the original color, which are produced by companies which
specialize in making ancient building materials. The bricks will
be laid using original techniques.
</P>
<P>
The renovation work, which started at the end of 1992, is the
Forbidden City's biggest overhaul project since the founding of
new China in 1949, Pei said. Total investment for the project is
is 3.5 million yuan (about 420,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Some 1,600 meters of wall, or about half of the total length,
will be repaired, Pei said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Parties Raise More Soft Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Major political parties in
the United States raised more 'soft money' in the first half of 1997
than they did during the same period of the last presidential
election cycle, the government reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Republicans raised 21.7 million dollars from January to
June, up from 16.6 million dollars in soft money during the first
half of 1995, when the Republican Party was amassing funds for the
presidential race, according to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
Democrats collected 13.7 million dollars, compared to 10.8
million dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Soft money is at the center of a current fund-raising
controversy.
</P>
<P>
Soft money comes in large donations that are unregulated and
unlimited. Soft money, exempt from the 25,000-dollar-a-year legal
contribution limit on donations from individuals, comes from rich
businessmen, corporations and unions that typically give five- and
six-figure checks to political parties.
</P>
<P>
The money can be used for generic party-building activities
like voter outreach, but not for supporting candidates.
</P>
<P>
Government watchdog groups have long criticized soft money as a
way for special interests to gain access into the political
system. Congress may soon take up a bill that would ban the
donations.
</P>
<P>
Insurance companies and tobacco firms were the biggest
contributors of soft money to the Republicans during the first
half of 1997, while Democratic Party committees received most of
their soft money from labor unions, lawyers and lobbyists,
according to an analysis by the watchdog group Common Cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0200 GMT, September 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Monday that it would
not hold further senior talks between Washington and Pyongyang
because of "unacceptable demands" from the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The State Department said, however, working-level discussions
between U.S. and DPRK officials would continue so that deadlock
for four-party peace talks could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
The State Department made the announcement after the four-party
preparatory meeting broke down in New York last Friday. The four
parties include the DPRK, South Korea, the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE -- Forces loyal to Congolese President Pascal Lissouba
Sunday carried out several helicopter raids on positions held by
his rival former Congolese President Sassou Nguesso in the capital
Brazzaville, said a report reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Three helicopter gunships are said to have taken part in the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
The authorities in the nearby Kinshasa, the capital of the
Democratic Republic of Congo, have suspended official crossings on
the Congo River.
</P>
<P>
The incident follows the failure of peace talks between the
delegations representing the two sides in Garbon a week ago.
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here Monday that the
cooperative relations between China and Russia are conducive to
peace and stability in the region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Anatoly
Chubais, Li said Sino-Russian relations have developed well in
recent years as the two countries have scored progress in their
cooperation in various areas.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the partnership of strategic coordination
between the two countries based on equality and mutual trust
oriented to the 21st century not only adapts to the new changes in
the international situation, but is also in the fundamental
interests of the two peoples, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Both Li and Chubais are in Hong Kong to attend the annual
meetings of the World Bank Group and the International Monetary
Fund, which are to open tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN - Jordanian police stepped up security around the Israeli
embassy here Monday after two Israeli security guards were lightly
wounded by a gunman outside Israeli ambassador's residence about
three kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
The streets near the embassy were blocked off and this would
remain until Tuesday morning, a patrolling police officer who
refused to be named told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Although the shooting took place near the ambassador's
residence, which was the former Israeli embassy, Jordanian police
still decided to tighten security around the embassy in case of
new violence, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
At about 7:30 local time (04:30 GMT) this morning, a man on a
vehicle passing by the ambassador's residence took out a gun and
shot at the security guards of the residence who were on routine
inspection duty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
