<HEADLINE> Lions Clubs International Helps Chinese Blind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Li Tanshi, a 52-year-old
Chinese farmer with cataracts, regained his eyesight after an
operation paid for by Sight First China Action (SFCA).
</P>
<P>
The SFCA campaign, which mainly aims at helping Chinese people
cure or prevent cataract disease with 15 million US dollars funded
by the Lions Club International (LCI) and some special government
funds, is carried out by the China Disabled Persons'
Federation (CDPF) and the Ministry of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
Li Tanshi comes from the Luliang mountainous region, one of the
most impoverished areas in China. People of all ages there develop
cataracts, Li said, and it is not unusual for whole families to
have the disease.
</P>
<P>
China has nine million blind people, including four million
with cataracts, according to Han Jibin, an official from CDPF.
Han added that the population with cataract grows by 400,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the blind live in rural areas and have limited access
to medical treatment. In China, there are still 500 county-level
hospitals without ophthalmology departments and some 70 percent of
the country's optometrists live in the cities.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has paid special attention to the plight
of the blind. From 1988 to 1996, some 1.75 million patients with
cataract have regained their eyesight through operations organized
by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and LCI have signed an agreement to
perform some 1.75 million cataract surgeries, to train 1,1000
optometrists and to build up ophthalmology departments in 100
county hospitals in the coming five years. The project will cost
165.48 million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
