<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng said here
today that as much as the developing countries need the developed
countries, the developed countries can not stand without the
developing countries because the world economy is an interrelated
whole.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the 1997 Annual Meetings of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) here this
morning, Li said, after several decades' efforts, the overall
strength of developing countries has increased remarkably, their
international status has risen and the prospects of their
economic growth look promising.
</P>
<P>
"The rise of developing countries is a far-reaching event in
the present-day world," he noted. "It has smashed the monopoly of
world affairs by a few countries and lent a powerful push behind
the movement towards a multipolar world."
</P>
<P>
He called attention to the fact that 1.3 billion people in the
developing world are still struggling in poverty.
</P>
<P>
He said that economic disparities among countries are
staggering as the gap between the rich and the poor continues to
widen and the unjust and inequitable international economic order
still puts interests of the developing countries in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
"If these problems remain unresolved, the developing countries
can not become developed, neither can the existing developed
countries sustain their growth," Li said.
</P>
<P>
To sustain their prosperity, the developed countries must have
markets for their goods, outlets for their capital and suppliers
of raw materials they need, on all of which they must look to the
developing countries for answers.
</P>
<P>
If the developing countries enjoy economic development and
social stability, this will increase the capacity of world market,
create more commercial and job opportunities for all countries and
generate tremendous benefits, Li added.
</P>
<P>
Conversely, if their economy is sluggish and society turbulent,
there will be no peace and tranquillity in the world, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The prosperity and affluence of a small number of countries can
not last long on the basis of poverty and backwardness of the
majority countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
"When we approach this issue, we must have in mind
cross-century development and entire mankind," Li said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Puts Forward Six Propositions for Helping Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng
today set forth the following six propositions of principle for
helping developing countries when addressing the opening ceremony
of the 1997 Annual Meetings of the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund (IMF) here:
</P>
<P>
First, full attention should be given to the urgent development
needs of the developing countries;
</P>
<P>
Second, extensive cooperation should be conducted on the basis
of equality and mutual benefit;
</P>
<P>
Third, the right of every country to independently choose its
social system, mode to development and lifestyle should be
respected;
</P>
<P>
Fourth, countries should learn from each other and complement
each other with respective advantages;
</P>
<P>
Fifth, it is essential to choose a development road suited to
one's own national conditions; and
</P>
<P>
Sixth, international cooperation in financial field should be
reinforced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
