<HEADLINE> 66,000 Mine Workers Laid off in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 66,000 miners, or 38
percent of the total mining workforce, have been laid off since
the government began to implement changes in the mining industry
in August, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Due to the absence of modern technology and low profits, the
coal and nonferrous metal mines -- the pillar industries in
Romania -- have received subsidies from the government every year.
</P>
<P>
Romania has recently decided to close down 30 mines between the
years 1998-2000, which will cost some 1,200 billion lei (about 160
million U.S. dollars), a senior official of the Industry and Trade
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Besides laying off unnecessary workers, the government is also
taking measures to improve the technology, renew the equipment,
and raise working efficiency and benefits of the mines, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
President Emil Constantinescu said at a rally on August 2 in
the Jiu Valley Coal, the biggest coal operation in the country,
"We must straighten out the problems in the Jiu Valley Coal
operation. We should not continue to perpetuate a situation of
low profits and dependence on subsidies."
</P>
<P>
Romania has set up three special agencies to deal with the
problem re-employing the sacked workers, asking medium- and
small-sized enterprises to absorb more of them.
</P>
<P>
Every sacked worker is eligible to receive a relief fund of
12-15 million lei (about 1,600-2,000 dollars) from the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
