<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Considers China Outstanding in Global Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China is an outstanding
participant in world trade, a Panamanian official said today.
</P>
<P>
Juan Jovana, director of the Center of National Studies of the
University of Panama (IDEN), said in an interview that China, the
third most important user of the Panama Canal after the United
States and Japan, provides great economic opportunities for Panama
and other Central American countries.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts believe China will replace Japan as an economic
superpower in Asia next century, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jovana added this has prompted many countries to maintain
better relations with the Asian giant.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, he stressed that out of their short-term
interests, a group of small countries are strengthening ties with
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"Taking advantage of short-term benefits from Taiwan may harm
our relations with China, which can be our most important partner
in the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
Panama's position is more crucial than other nations, because
Hong Kong has become the biggest supplier of Colon's free trade
zone in Panama after it returned to China in July, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent report on the Panamanian trade, the free
trade zone in Colon, 80 kilometers west of this city, imported a
total of 5 billion U.S. dollars of goods, with 1.3 billion coming
from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The IDEN director denied that the Panamanian authorities have
not strengthened ties with China. "If China bans Panamanian ships
entering its ports or if our businessmen are denied entrance to
Hong Kong, that would be worrisome for Panamanian economy," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
