<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Israeli Potash JV Close to Signing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations for
establishment of a Sino-Israeli potash joint venture have entered
the final crucial stage, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources from the Ministry of Chemical
Industry as saying that two sides are striving to sign an
agreement for the establishment before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations have lasted about a decade. If the agreement
is signed at the end of the year, production may start in five
years after the plant is built.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the potash joint venture, which will
be situated on a salt lake desert near Golmud in northwest China's
Qinghai Province, will require a total investment of 4.6 billion
yuan and will be able to produce 800,000 tons of potash or
potassium carbonate annually when completed.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture will be jointly financed by United
Development Industry Co. of Israel, and Mingda Corporation of the
the Chinese Ministry of Chemical Industry and Qinghai Salt Lake
Industrial Group Co.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture will apply Israeli techniques to
manufacturing potash for the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Potash is very important for grain harvests, and China's
agricultural development is creating a huge market for
potash-based fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
China now needs 3.5 million tons of potash a year for
agricultural use, but has to import 2.2 million tons annually from
Canada, Israel, Jordan, Russia and other countries to fill the
domestic production gap. By the end of this century, the country's
annual demand for potash for agricultural use is expected to hit
five million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
