<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Capital to Step Up Reforms in Small Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will hasten the
development of its small commercial enterprises by merging them
into bigger group companies, setting up a modern enterprise system
and closing those heavily in debt.
</P>
<P>
The first step the city will take is to encourage small
companies to cluster together and urge big ones to take in small
partners to form large group companies, said Gong Li,
deputy-director of the Municipal Committee of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to build two or three large commercial groups
with an annual income of over 10 billion yuan by the year 2000,
Gong said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing also expects to see more small retail shops merging
into chain-shops and increase the proportion of their sales volume
to the city's total from the current 4.5 percent to 18 percent in
years, she explained.
</P>
<P>
The small companies are also encouraged to establish a modern
enterprise system, with the focus on building a cooperative
share-holding system. More than 60 percent of the small
enterprises in the city are expected to adopt the shareholding
system by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Various forms of ownership will be applied to small enterprises
to make them more open and flexible, Gong said.
</P>
<P>
Those which are deeply in debt and cannot make up deficits and
increase profits should be sold in accordance with relevant
policies or declare bankruptcy, she said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of small commercial enterprises
in Beijing amounts to over 90 percent of the total, with 7,700
small shops reporting an average annual revenue of less than
50,000 yuan (about 6,000 US dollars) each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
