<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Mint Produces Platinum Coins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Mint is starting
the public sale of the nation's first-ever platinum bullion coins
on Tuesday in one-ounce and tenth-ounce denominations, said an
Associated Press report today.
</P>
<P>
Sales of uncirculated American Eagle platinum coins in
half-ounce and quarter-ounce denominations will begin in October.
</P>
<P>
All the coins bear a portrait of the Statue of Liberty on front
and a soaring bald eagle on back. They will be sold at market
price, currently around 425 dollars for one ounce, plus a premium
which varies.
</P>
<P>
The 100-dollar face value of the one-ounce coin is the highest
denomination ever made by the U.S. Mint. The half-ounce coin will
bear a face value of 50 dollars. The quarter-ounce and tenth-ounce
will bear face values of 25 and 10 dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Congress authorized the sale of platinum coins last year and the
U.S. Mint has sold 28,000 ounces to authorized wholesale
purchasers.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Mint has been selling gold and silver bullion coins
since 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Authorities Signs Agreement Against Hooliganism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch authorities and
the football association on Monday signed agreement in an effort
to fight against the soccer hooliganism.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for more co-ordination between government,
local authorities and the police, and recognises hooliganism as a
national rather than a localised problem.
</P>
<P>
The proposals include higher level surveillance of hooligans,
co-ordination over stadium bans and an insistence that "high risk"
matches are played in the afternoon, rather than in the evening.
</P>
<P>
The new agreement follows last week's decision by Ajax and
Feyenoord to ban away supporters from attending games between the
two clubs.
</P>
<P>
An Ajax supporter was killed by Feynoord fans in March, the
first death in the Netherlands linked to soccer hooliganism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
