<HEADLINE> State-Owned Enterprises Seeking Overseas Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Overseas funding is becoming
increasingly more attractive to the state-owned enterprises in
Shenyang, an industrial base in northeast China. Latest
statistics show overseas investment has been drawn to 37 percent
of the firms in the city.
</P>
<P>
From 1992 to 1995, the city government approved 2,415
foreign-funded projects, accounting for 70 percent of such
projects in Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
The recently concluded International Trade Fair of Shenyang
brought in from overseas entrepreneurs 1.2 billion US dollars of
contractual funds, 65 percent of which were involved in industry.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang Mayor Mu Suixin said that in order to build a new
enterprise system that conforms to the international trend,
Shenyang's large and medium-sized enterprises should introduce
funding, new products, new technology and modern management modes
from overseas.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to create a more favorable environment for overseas
investment in the city, where more than 340 large and medium-sized
enterprises are located, the city government has canceled some 130
unreasonable fees.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 60 percent of Shenyang's industrial profit comes
from foreign-backed ventures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
