<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Sheds More Light on Mafia-Politician Link in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A Rome court trial of former
Christian Democrat Minister Calogero Mannino shed more light today
on the strong links between the Sicilian Mafia and Italian
politicians in 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Gioacchino Pennino, an ex-Mafia affiliate, told the court that
the Mafia "inspired and conditioned" many of the political
candidates of those years in Palermo, capital of Sicily.
</P>
<P>
Without Mafia support, it was impossible to enter and perform
the public service, Pennino claimed.
</P>
<P>
Pennino, a well-known Palermo doctor, named a number of former
Christian Democrats who had "close" relations with the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
The Mafia has a tradition to turn to political parties, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "first the Monarchists, then the Liberals, the the
Christian Democrats and finally the Socialists, for whom the Cosa
Nostra bosses gave an order to vote en masses in the 1987 general
election."
</P>
<P>
Pennino said that he used to frequented Christian Democrat
circles but never agreed to run for political office.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't want to make it even easier for the Mafia to
blackmail me, " he claimed.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had no knowledge on whether Salvo Lima, a
powerful Christian Democrat and the leader of former Italian Prime
Minister Giulio Andreotti's faction in Sicily, was a Mafia-linked
member of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Lima, who was killed by the Mafia in 1992, has been alleged as
the main link between Andreotti and the Mafia bosses.
</P>
<P>
Andreotti, a life senator and the seven-times premier denies
all charges against him, saying they are part of a Mafia plot to
revenge him for crackdowns on organized crime by governments he
headed.
</P>
<P>
Andreotti's trial began in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Souvenirs on HK's Return to China Still in Great Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Uncle Wang, 72, waited all night
outside a post office here to buy a set of commemorative stamps
just issued to mark Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
"Compared to the 150 years we Chinese spent waiting for Hong
Kong's return to the motherland, standing here for several hours
is nothing," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Around the time of handover day on July 1, souvenirs honoring
the event flooded Chinese markets and department stores. Nearly
three months later, demands from all over China continue to pour
in to distributors for the endless array of watches, pens, rings,
calendars, caps, T-shirts, porcelainware and mugs.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 types of stamps, commemorative coins and magnetic
cards also have been issued, according to conservative estimates.
</P>
<P>
Some of the stamps, especially those issued by the government
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), broke sales
records, according to an official. Stamps bearing designs related
to the historic event issued by more than 20 countries and regions
are also hotly sought after by collectors.
</P>
<P>
The number of stamp-collectors has increased by about 20
percent in Hong Kong since last year, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
When issuing gold and silver commemorative coins, the People's
Bank of China (PBC) had to send security guards to look after the
queues of buyers.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, the 100 million new coins featuring a bauhinia
flower rather than the crown of the Queen of England were snatched
up in just over a month by citizens, forcing the Hong Kong
Government to issue an additional 160 million.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of commemorative magnetic cards for telephones, subways
and parks are treasured by collectors, the official added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, many people are still searching for copies of Chinese
newspapers dated July 1, particularly those specially-made
editions, including a miniature version of the People's Daily,
silk copies of the July 1 Shanghai Wenhuibao and China News
Pictorial, and even 97' 24k gold editions of Hong Kong's "Ta Kung
Pao" to honor HK return to the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Preservation Method Keeps Coconuts Fresh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese researchers and
technicians in south China's Hainan Province have developed a new
preservation technique which keeps newly-picked coconuts
fresh for a longer time.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from China Tropical Agriculture and Coconut
Institute, in cooperation with technicians from a local coconut
processing factory in Wenchang, have reported success with the
method of soaking just-picked coconuts in mineral water, then
shaping them into different artistic designs before freezing and
packaging them.
</P>
<P>
The method has increased the expiration term of green coconuts
after picking from only seven days to 40 days.
</P>
<P>
At a recent trade fair of fruits and vegetables held in Hainan,
dubbed the "island of coconuts" and also a leading coconut
producer of China, the preserved coconuts sold like hot cakes.
Orders for 150,000 coconuts were made on the first day of the
fair, said a local source. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
