<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Household Workshops Growing in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Every morning, Chen Huili, a
46-year-old laid-off worker in Shanghai, picks up her knitting
after finishing the daily chores.
</P>
<P>
"I am satisfied that I not only can take care of my home, but
also earn some money by knitting," she said.
</P>
<P>
On Dongjiadu Street in Shanghai's Nanshi District, nearly 200
laid-off workers like Chen are involved in cottage industries of
knitting, sewing and making packing boxes, earning an average of
about 500 yuan each month.
</P>
<P>
According to a local official, the district government plans to
develop up to 800 varieties of such home-based workshops. The
local government has earmarked a special fund of two million yuan
for the project, and formed a company to lease machinery and
materials to the workers.
</P>
<P>
The cottage industries have great development potential as
they attract more redundant workers and do not create pollution,
said Gu Junyi, the director of Shanghai Labour Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai boasts large numbers of skilled folk craftsmen and a
history of traditional crafts such as embroidery, woollen
needlepoint tapestry and dough modelling. Some of the laid-off
workers also make tourist souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Enzhen, a local economist, said that the handicrafts can
also be expanded to include products of higher value, including
software development, home-based consulting services, and
industrial design.
</P>
<P>
However, reemployment training is key to a healthy, sustained
development of the household industry, as most redundant workers
have no special skills, according to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
Chen Hong, a well-known sweater designer, started out by
knitting and selling sweaters at home and now runs 30 chain
stores. "I am ready to teach my knitting skills to laid-off
workers," she said.
</P>
<P>
The local government will offer a three-year cut in taxes for
the cottage industries, and the laid-offs doing the work can
retain their old-age and medical insurance benefits from their
former jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970923.0273 </DOCNO>
