<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mexico City, September 22 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
Foreign Investments Boom in Venezuela
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Foreign capitals flowing into Venezuela amounted
to 63.99 million U.S. dollars last August, representing a 300
percent increase over July.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Investment Office (SIEX, for its Spanish short)
said in a statement that manufacturing industry ranked first
foreign currency earner with 58.65 million dollars, followed
by commerce with 3.57 million dollars and agriculture,
765,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
SIEX considered that application of the economic reform has
restored long-lost confidence in the country and fueled the
productive sector, which attracts increasing inflowing capitals.
</P>
<P>
Mexico-Nicaragua Free Trade Agreement Praised
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The just signed Free Trade Agreement between
Nicaragua and Mexico is a "round success" to benefit primarily
the agricultural sector, expressed the minister of the Institute
of Nicaragua for Agrarian Reform, Virgilio Gurdian.
</P>
<P>
The accord was inked last week during Nicaraguan president
Arnoldo Aleman visit's to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The Agreement sets up a 5,000-ton annual quote for duty-free
exports of beef to Mexico (with a 5 percent annual increase);
5,000 tons of milk added to those Nicaragua currently produces
for the company Nestle of Mexico; 4,000 tons of dry beans with a
3-percent anual increase, and 500 tons of cheese.
</P>
<P>
Copper Production Grows in Chile
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Output of Chilean fine copper from "Minera
Escondida" boosted to 65,468 lengthy tons in August.
</P>
<P>
The accumulated production of the metal from the first copper
field of the country during the first 8 months rose to 609,000
lengthy tons, a 8.6 percent increase against 560,834 lenghty tons
produced in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In full 1996 "Minera Escondida" produced 841,000 lengthy tons
of copper, accounting for 26 percent of the total national output.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, Main Target for Foreign Investments in LA
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil ranked first Latin American country to get
foreign investments in 1996, reaching 9.5 billion dollars, the
United Nations Conference for Trade and Development (UNCTAD)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Acording to the conference, last year, foreign direct
investments to Latin America and the Caribbean swelled 52
percent, to 39 billion dollars, the highest increase for any
other developing region in the world.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela To Wipe Out Fuel Subsidies
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The government of Venezuela will present its
National Energy Policy on October 2 most likely to eliminate
all general, permanent and crossed fuel subsidies gradually.
</P>
<P>
This action will obviously translate into an increment of
prices.
</P>
<P>
The document will be debated and likely passed also on
the same day by the Nacional Council of Energy, before the
approval by president Rafael Caldera.
</P>
</TEXT>
