<HEADLINE> World Race Fleet Towards the Atlantic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Ten boats engaged in a close
battle all the way down the English Channel and Grant Dalton's
Merit Cup from Monaco led the Whitbread Round the World Race fleet
towards the Atlantic Ocean on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The changeable weather made some boats turn south across the
Bay of Biscay and others go straight into the Atlantic Ocean after
passing the north west tip of France.
</P>
<P>
In the first 30 hours of the race, wind conditions ranged from
as low as three knots and up as high as 30.
</P>
<P>
Four boats, EF Language, Toshiba steered by Chris Dickson,
Chessie Racing with Jim Allsopp in charge, and Merit Cup, have all
had a turn in the lead, with race favourite Toshiba having held
every position from first to last.
</P>
<P>
Reports from on board have been as varied as the conditions
they have experienced, with the crew of the American entry Chessie
Racing, "yahooing" as they hit 18 knots.
</P>
<P>
The first leg, of nine, takes the fleet 7,350 nautical miles
down the Atlantic Ocean to Cape Town in South Africa, where they
are expected to arrive on October 22.  
</P>
</TEXT>
