<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA Ban Anderlecht Over Bribes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Belgium's biggest club
Anderlecht have been banned from all European club competitions
due to alleged bribes to referees in 1983 and 1984, European
soccer body UEFA said in a statement on Monday.
</P>
<P>
UEFA said that they had made the decision "for ethical and
moral reasons arising from incidents in 1983 and 1984 concerning
bribery of referees". The decision was made after an executive
committee meeting led by President Lennart Johansson.
</P>
<P>
The Belgians, the UEFA Cup winners in 1983 as well as Cup
Winners' Cup champions in 1976 and 1978, are in the UEFA
tournament this season. They lost their first round first leg
match 3-4 to Salzburg in Austria last week.
</P>
<P>
The club won the second leg of the 1984 semi-final 3-0 at home,
and 3-2 on aggregate, after England's Nottingham Forest had a goal
controversially disallowed and Anderlecht scored from a disputed
penalty.
</P>
<P>
Anderlecht earlier this month admitted to having paid Spanish
referee Guruceta Muro one million francs (27,000 U.S. dollars) for
that match. Muro died in a car crash in 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
