<HEADLINE> Latin America News Economic Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Public Deficit in Uruguay
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's annual public deficit last July
reached 327 million U.S. dollars, equivalent to 1.6 percent of
the national Gross Domestic Product (GDP), according to the
Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing Contracts in Mexico
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Manufacturing industry in Mexico registered
8.43 billion-dollar trade balance deficit in January-July 1997,
the Bank of Mexico reported.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the "maquiladoras" (foreign companies employing
Mexican labor force and facilities primarily to produce goods
for exportation) generated foreign currency up to 6.17 billion
dollars during January-July, which helped to lower the total
manufacturing trade balance deficit by 73 percent.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural Exports Up in Costa Rica
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica`s agricultural exports for the first 7
months rose 7.24 percent as compared to that in the same period
1996.
</P>
<P>
Sales of the sector went up from 829.73 million dollars in
the first 7 months of 1996 to 889.84 million in the same period
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Coffee and pineapple overseas sales jumped 12.2 percent and
40.2 percent respectively in the first 7 months.
</P>
<P>
Investments to Mines in Chile Reach 4.8 Billion
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Roughly 4.8 billion U.S. dollars will be invested
in several domestic and foreign mining companies based in Chile,
over the next 3 years.
</P>
<P>
According to Chile`s Copper Commission (COCHILCO), a large
share of the total will go to projects in "Dona Ines de
Collahuasi", in the first region, and in "Los Pelambres" in the
fourth region. Both projects will need a total capital of 3
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Such high-ranging projects will come altogether with others
in San Antonio, Lomas Bayas and Tesoro-Leonor. All these 3 plans
will require investments of above 1.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Food Imports Raised in Colombia
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- Foodstuff imports to Colombia rose 26.8
percent last July to 2.35 million tons, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
During that month roughly 497,828 tons of foodstuff of
agricultural and livestock origin entered the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
