<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red-Crowned Cranes Raised in Shenyang Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China's sole red-crowned
crane breeding center, located in the city zoo in this capital of
northeast China's Liaoning province, has raised 239 of the
endangered red-crowned cranes, a species under top state
protection.
</P>
<P>
The 239 birds account for over half of those cranes
artificially bred and raised in the country since 1989, when the
center bred its first red-crowned crane.
</P>
<P>
The red-crowned crane is regarded as a symbol of longevity and
prosperity in Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
The crane breeding center has conducted research on freezing of
the red-crowned crane's semen, returning the artificially-bred
cranes to nature, and the reproduction of the crane, said Liu
Dajun, the zoo's manager.
</P>
<P>
The center has also established relatively complete
genealogical files on the cranes mated here to prevent inbreeding,
Liu said. It now has 13 pairs of red-crowned cranes used for
breeding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
