<HEADLINE> U.N. Officials Welcome Turner's Contribution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- High-ranking officials
of the United Nations have welcomed the one billion U.S. dollar
contribution by U.S. media tycoon Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
"All U.N. agencies will come together to ensure the best use of
this extraordinary endorsement," said several chiefs of U.N.
bodies in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
Ted Turner, the Vice Chairman of Time Warner Inc. announced
last Thursday his decision to contribute a total of one billion
dollars in a ten-year timespan to the U.N. for its humanitarian
work.
</P>
<P>
The fund "comes at a crucial moment for the U.N. which grapples
with dwindling resources to meet a growing array of vital needs,"
said UNICEF (U. N. Chidren's Fund) Director Carol Bellamy, UNFPA
(U.N. Fund Population Fund) Director Nafis Sadik and UNDP (U.N.
Development Program) Administrator James Gustave Speth.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan praised Turner's
action, saying his offer demonstrated his belief in the U.N.
organization and international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"I hope it will inspire governments to pay what they owe,"
Annan emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The country owing the U.N. the most is the one which houses the
U.N.. The United States has so far accumulated its membership dues
to some 1.5 billion dollars, more than half of the annual U.N.
budget.
</P>
<P>
The funds from Turner "will not offset the 1.5 billion dollars
that the united States owes the United Nations because the world
body cannot accept contributions from private citizens for that
purpose," said the spokesman for Annan.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address to the 52nd session of the U.N. Assembly
here today, Annan again called those indebted member states to
liquidate their arrears and to pay their future assessments "in
full, on time and without conditions."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton in his address to the U.N. Assembly
today did not say when U.S. arrears will be cleared, but rather
hinted that the question should be solved by Congress first.
</P>
<P>
Annan had said that the U.N. cannot accept the conditions put
forward by the U.S. Congress as they would jeopardize U.S. image
and aggravate tensions between the U.S. and other U.N. member
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
