<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- One of Australia's two biggest stevedoring companies has
told the Howard government to "put up or shut up" on waterfront
reform, describing recent rhetoric as "unhelpful" and "becoming
boring", and said the government had "no proper understanding of
the complexity of the whole subject."
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The number of New South Wales Lower House seats would be cut
by six to maximize Labor's reelection chances under a proposal
adopted unanimously Monday by the cabinet. The premier, who took
the plan to cabinet, will ask caucus today to approve the cut to
93 seats.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The federal government and employers last night attacked a
new push by the Australian Council of Trade Unions for a 20-a-week
Australian dollars pay rise for more than 1.5 million workers,
warning that it would increase unemployment and inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The federal government moved last night to open Australia's
four billion Australian dollars (2.88 billion US dollars) local
telephone market to full competition by forcing Telstra, the
telecommunication giant of the country, to underwrite the cost of
switching a customer's phone number to another carrier.  
</P>
</TEXT>
