<HEADLINE> US Budget Deficit Going to Be Smallest Since 1974 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The budget deficit of U.S.
government totaled 34.6 billion dollars in August and the red ink
is on track to be the smallest in 23 years, the U.S. Treasury
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The department reported that revenue totaled 103.5 billion
dollars last month and expenditures was 138.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the U.S. government has received about 1.4
trillion dollars in revenue and spent 1.48 trillion dollars. It
brought the shortfall for the first 11 months of the budget year
to 71.3 billion dollars, 50 percent less than during the same
period of fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
With a substantial surplus expected in September, the last
month of this fiscal year, the U.S. government should have little
trouble recording a deficit for all of fiscal 1997 at or under the
37 billion dollars projected last month by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
It would be the smallest since 1974 and would mark the fifth
consecutive improvement since President Clinton took office in
1993.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit of the U.S. government swelled to a record
290 billion dollars in fiscal year of 1992.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. budget deficit was 107.4 billion dollars in fiscal
1996 and the Clinton administration is projecting it will increase
to 58.3 billion in 1998 and won't decline below the 1997 level
until 2001.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton and the U.S. Congress reached an agreement
earlier this year to eliminate all the deficit by 2002 and a
balanced-budget bill was signed into law in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
