<HEADLINE> U.S. "Concerned" over Arab League on Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States said it
was "concerned" over a statement by the Arab League calling for
lifting sanctions against Libya.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply concerned by what appears to be an Arab League
call to violate sanctions against Libya. If there are violations,
it would be a matter for the immediate attention of the U.N.
Security Council," State Department spokesman James Foley said at
a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League voted in Cairo on Sunday to allow flights
carrying "the political leadership and official Libyan
delegations" to land on member-nations territory.
</P>
<P>
the statement also urged 21 Arab nations to permit Libyan
flights for humanitarian reasons, such as transport of people to
an annual Muslim pilgrimage in Mecca.
</P>
<P>
But Foley said Libya continues to defy the will of the
international community by refusing to comply with U.N. Security
Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions were imposed in 1992 after Libya refused to
hand over for trial two suspects wanted in Britain and the United
States for the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over the Scotland in
1988. The blast killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Libya has proposed to hand over the suspects to the World
Court in the Hague, Netherland, but the proposal was rejected by
the United States and Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
